<1ST_LINE>u a AM-People-AbbieHoffman     06-19 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Abbie Hoffman,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abbie Hoffman Smoking Mad At Continental Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Activist Abbie Hoffman said Sunday he was ordered
off a Continental Airlines plane at O'Hare International Airport
after a flight attendant unjustly accused him of smoking marijuana
in the lavatory.
   Hoffman, the 51-year-old former Yippie leader, said ``some very
strange things'' seem to happen to him in Chicago, where 20 years
ago he was a key organizer of the August 1968 anti-Vietnam War
protests at the Democratic National Convention.
   The incident occurred late Friday afternoon just after he had
boarded a flight bound for Newark, N.J., after visiting Chicago to
meet with Playboy magazine editors, Hoffman said by telephone from
Northampton, Mass., where he was speaking at an anti-nuclear power
rally.
   Minutes before takeoff, Hoffman said, he went into the lavatory
to take some prescription medicine. Suddenly, the fire alarm bells
started ringing.
   ``Then the stewardess pushes in the door with her knee like a
stormtrooper, and starts shouting, `You've been smoking
marijuana,''' Hoffman said. ``I said, `Like hell, bring on the
dogs. I'm not smoking anything.'''
   ``She's lucky I didn't have my pants down.''
   Hoffman said he was ordered off the plane, and as he was getting
off some passengers asked for his autograph.
   He said he was briefly questioned by an official who didn't
identify himself, and then allowed to board Continental's next
flight to Newark. But the airline lost his carry-on bag, he said.
   Ned Walker, a Continental spokesman, said it was company policy
not to release passenger names, but confirmed that a male passenger
was ordered off the Newark-bound flight.
   He said several crew members and passengers ``smelled a burning
odor coming from the lavatory'' after the smoke alarms went off
while the plane was refueling.
   ``Smoking on the ground or in a lavatory is in violation of
federal aviation regulations and could conceivably put the safety
of passengers and crew members at risk,'' said Walker, reached at
his home in Houston.
   ``The passenger admitted to our personnel that he was in the
lavatory smoking a Cuban cigarette,'' said Walker, adding that he
did not know the cigarette's contents.
   The man then ``apologized and assured our personnel that he
would conduct himself in accordance with the law,'' Walker said.
   In his Northampton appearance, Hoffman criticized actress Jane
Fonda's recent apology for her 1972 trip to North Vietnam and
called her ``a fink.''
   Fonda last week expressed regret for her trip to Hanoi, which
has embittered many veterans and conservatives for years.
   ``The times were extreme and maybe what we did was extreme but
you need the generals to apologize for what they did,'' Hoffman
told a crowd of about 300.
</TEXT>
