<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CordCure 1stAdd   06-19 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cord Cure, 1st Add,0729</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CORAL GABLES: jellied candy.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   It works like an intricate telephone cable, with millions of
microwires carrying messages to and from body organs and
extremities. But if these ``wires'' fray or snap, they can't be
spliced, glued or soldered.
   Injury prevents brain messages of balance and movement to reach
the limbs. Messages of pain, touch and temperature can't reach the
brain.
   ``You sit there and rot and wait to die,'' Sandy Valentino, 24,
paralyzed seven years ago in a car accident, said of her initial
devastation. ``When you don't die, you pick up the pieces and
decide what you're going to do with the rest of your life. Despair
makes you search for something, anything, to try.''
   Miss Valentino is now working to build her arm muscles in the
biofeedback unit at the Miami Project.
   When the spinal cord is injured, bleeding and swelling kill off
the nerve fibers, and the eventual scars block messages to and from
the brain. Any cure must come from regenerating the nerves to grow
through or around the scar.
   The problem is that spinal nerves are biologically programmed to
grow only in the fetal stage. Peripheral nerves, however, such as
those found in arms and legs, can grow back, and researchers are
trying to transplant them inside the spinal cord.
   In 1982, Dr. Albert Aguayo of Montreal's McGill University
Medical School grafted cells from a rat's leg nerve into its
damaged spinal cord. The nerve grew but stopped at the other side
of the scar without making a functioning connection.
   At the Miami Project, one promising research effort toward nerve
regeneration is being moved to Sweden because of intense feeling on
abortion here.
   The particular research implants cells from aborted human
fetuses into rats to see if new spinal cord nerves will sprout. Dr.
Ake Seiger, director of basic research at the Miami Project, also
worked on the Swedish research teams that used fetal cells to
regenerate brain cells in victims of Parkinson's and Alzheimer's
diseases.
   Anti-abortion groups in the United States oppose using fetal
cells, and the National Institutes of Health in April barred
federal researchers from transplanting fetal brain tissue into
Parkinson's patients.
   Arthur Caplan, head of the Center for Biomedical Research at the
University of Minnesota, backs the use of fetal cells despite the
abortion debate.
   ``If it works, it would revolutionize medicine. It would offer
cures and help to people who had nothing. It will be almost
irresistible to use, no matter what the ethical questions are,''
Caplan said.
   In other spinal cord research:
   _ Neuroscientist Paul Reier at the University of Florida in
Gainesville is working with rat fetal cells to build a bridge
around or through a spinal cord injury;
   _ Scientists using fetal cells on a thin splint got a damaged
peripheral nerve that controls the toe of a rat to grow back into
the spinal cord, where it made connections to restore function. The
work was done by neurologists Jerry Silver of Case-Western Reserve
University and Michael Kliot of Columbia Presbyterian Hospital.
   _ At Purdue University, biophysicist Richard Borgens has
implanted tiny batteries above spinal cord injuries, creating
low-level electrical pulses that encourage nerves to grow through
scar tissue. Of 200 paralyzed guinea pigs implanted, 25 percent
showed some movement, Borgens said.
   When he played for the Dolphins, Nick Buoniconti was the heart
of a unit of overachievers known as the No-Name Defense that helped
Miami win two Super Bowls and go unbeaten in the 1972 season.
   After his son's injury, he helped coordinate existing research
and assembled a team of doctors to try to beat paralysis.
   In 2{ years, the Miami Project has raised $8 million and has
spent $6 million on research. It hopes to raise $20 million for a
self-sustaining endowment.
   ``We've replaced the word despair with hope. We've given science
an opportunity,'' said the elder Buoniconti.
   His son just completed his first full semester at the University
of Miami, where he made the dean's list as a psychology major.
   ``There's a great possibility I'll live and die in this
wheelchair,'' Buoniconti said. ``But there's no reason to feel
sorry for myself. I've been taught that in all adversity, never
give up. I wouldn't know how to give up.''
</TEXT>
