<1ST_LINE>u a AM-GayParade     06-19 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gay Parade,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oklahoma Has First Gay Pride Parade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state's first gay pride march was held
Sunday in Oklahoma City without any incidents, despite rumors that
the Ku Klux Klan might attempt to disrupt the event.
   ``Here in Oklahoma, because it is the buckle of the Bible Belt,
the gay rights movement has been very slow,'' said parade chairman
Andy Southam. ``We're hoping that with this first march people's
thinking will start to move forward.''
   Parade organizers said nearly 400 lesbians and gay men came from
Oklahoma and nearby states participated, as did Jeff Levi,
executive director of the National Gay and Lesbian Task Force, who
flew back from an AIDS conference in Stockholm, Sweden.
   ``This first march is a coming of age for the local community,''
Levi said. ``It's important in coalescing a feeling of community
and a feeling of pride. Particulary during the AIDS crisis, it is
important to be doing positive things when so many people are sick
and dying.''
   A group of people with AIDS were honorary grand marshals for the
parade. Other participants carried balloons that Southam said
represented people who could not attend because of social pressures.
</TEXT>
