<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Paxton     06-19 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Paxton,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AP Albany Bureau Chief of 29 Years Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTHPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norris Paxton, who headed The Associated
Press bureau in Albany, N.Y., for nearly three decades, has died of
cancer. He was 87.
   Paxton, who moved to Madison 16 years ago, died Saturday at a
nursing home here where he had spent his last five days.
   He was one of the wire service's youngest bureau chiefs when he
took charge of its Albany bureau in 1936. When he retired on March
31, 1966, Paxton was the AP's senior bureau administrator in years
of service.
   ``He set a standard of excellence for the reporters working for
him that has never been matched again,'' said Charles Dumas, the
chief capital correspondent during Paxton's tenure and now director
of communications for the New York state Senate.
   On his 20th anniversary at the bureau, Paxton won praise from
the Albany Knickerbocker News as ``a newspaperman's newspaper man.''
   Paxton was born in Richmond, Mo., and attended the College of
Emporia in Kansas, where he got his first taste of journalism doing
odd jobs for the Emporia Gazette.
   He worked at the Topeka State Journal, the Wichita Eagle, the
Pratt (Kansas) Tribune, the San Antonio Star and the Kansas City
Journal before joining the AP in Kansas City in 1926. He also
worked for the AP in New York before taking charge of the Albany
bureau.
   Paxton is survived by daughters Janet Cummings, a reporter, and
Laura Lee Nixon of Tokyo, three grandchildren and one great
grandchild.
   Funeral arrangements were not announced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
