<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Norris Paxton</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTHPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norris Paxton, who headed The Associated
Press bureau in Albany, N.Y., for nearly three decades, died
Saturday after a brief illness. He was 87.
   Paxton, who moved to Madison 16 years ago, died of cancer at a
nursing home here where he spent his last five days.
   He was one of the wire service's youngest bureau chiefs when he
took charge of its Albany bureau in 1936. When he retired on March
31, 1966, Paxton was the AP's senior bureau administrator in years
of service.
   Paxton was born in Richmond, Mo., and attended the College of
Emporia in Kansas, where he worked for the Emporia Gazette.
   He worked at the Topeka State Journal, the Wichita Eagle, the
Pratt (Kansas) Tribune, the San Antonio Star and the Kansas City
Journal before joining the AP in Kansas City in 1926. He also
worked for the AP in New York before taking charge of the Albany
bureau.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Salwa Rifai</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salwa Rifai, a Jordanian immigrant related by
marriage to the Jordanian prime minister Zaid Rifai, died Saturday
of injuries suffered in a motor vehicle accident June 11. She was
45.
   Her late husband, Hisham Rifai, was the Jordanian prime
minister's uncle, said Dr. Sabri El Farra, a physician and family
friend.
   Mrs. Rifai lived in Los Angeles as a permanent U.S. resident for
the past eight years and was in the process of securing U.S.
citizenship, El Farra said, and recently obtained her master's
degree in Mass Communtications at Cal State Northridge.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>James Houghton</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Capt. James O. Houghton, commanding
officer of the Naval Aerospace Medical Research Laboratory, died
Thursday in an automobile accident. He was 45.
   Houghton had commanded NAMRL since June 1985, and was scheduled
to leave his job July 1 to work at the Naval Medical Command in
Washington, D.C.
   A native of Littlefield, Texas, a graduate of Union College, he
earned his medical degree at Loma Linda University in California.
After a Philadelphia Naval Hospital intership, he was designated a
naval flight surgeon in 1970.
   Houghton, who was single, served with the First and Third Marine
Air Wings in Santa Ana, Calif., Vietnam and Okinawa, and had been
senior medical officer aboard the USS Oriskany and the USS Midway.
   Houghton conducted research in acceleration physiology at the
Naval Air Development Center in Warminister, Pa. He also worked as
a special assistant for aerospace medicine at the Naval Air Systems
Command in Washington, D.C.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Ed Montague</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALY CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ed Montague, a former shortstop with
the Cleveland Indians and a longtime scout with the New York and
San Francisco Giants, died Friday at the age of 82.
   Montague, a San Francisco nativer who signed Willie Mays with
the Giants when the team was in New York, worked for the Giants for
40 years, primarily as a scout. He played with the Indians from
1928-1935 and played for the San Francisco Seals' minor league
baseball team.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Philippe Dien</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnamese Archbishop Philippe Nguyen
Kim Dien, who defied communist attempts to control his country's
Roman Catholic Church, died June 8. He was 67.
   The official Vietnam News Agency, in a report monitored in
Bangkok, said Dien died of an illness at Cho Ray Hospital in Ho Chi
Minh City, formerly Saigon. It gave no cause of death.
   Dien was barred from work as a priest and put under house arrest
in 1984 for urging priests not to join the Committee for Solidarity
of Patriotic Vietnamese Catholics. The state had formed the group
the previous year, and critics said it was designed to control the
church.
   While under house arrest, Dien continued to circulate letters
among his parishioners, and authorities apparently made no serious
attempt to replace him. He remained under house arrest until his
death.
   The Vatican said Kim was born in March 1921 in Vinh Long. The
city was a traditional center of the Catholic Church in the Mekong
River Delta in southern Vietnam. He was ordained in July 1947 and
became a bishop in 1961, the Vatican said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Cesar Barrientos</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Cesar Barrientos, minister of the
treasury since Gen. Alfredo Stroessner siezed power in a 1954 coup,
died Friday. He was 82.
   The cause of death was not reported, but Barrientos had not
appeared in public since late last year and had received medical
treatment in recent months in Argentina.
   Barrientos was an army administrative officer when Stroessner
came to power and appointed him to the treasury post.
</TEXT>
