<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ChemicalFire 3rdLd-Writethru a0658 06-19 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chemical Fire, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0658,0821</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>At Least 275 Injured By Fumes From Chlorine Plant Blaze</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with six grafs to UPDATE with evacuations continuing,
up to 30,000 affected. Picks up 6th graf pvs ``Earlier, the...''
Deletes outdated figure from 18th graf pvs, ``All but...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of gallons of water failed
to control a chlorine plant blaze that raged for a second day
Saturday, sending clouds of gas over the city, injuring 275 people
and forcing the evacuation of up to 30,000 residents.
   The city's five pumpers were turned on the Advanced Laboratories
factory in hopes of ``turning the plant into a big swimming pool,''
said Fire Department spokesman Giorgio Placanico.
   The attempt to extinguish the blaze remained unsuccessful late
Saturday. Fire engulfed the four-story building, sending flames 100
feet high and spreading the chlorine cloud about two miles long and
four blocks wide.
   Seven of the 125 firefighters battling the blaze were injured
Saturday night. More were on call from neighboring towns, Placanico
said.
   ``We're flooding it with everything we have,'' he said.
   Placanico said 20,000 to 30,000 people were evacuated and buses
still were transporting residents away from the area early Sunday.
   Earlier, the city extended an evacuation order to one mile
around the plant and 1{ miles to the northeast, where winds carried
gas clouds hundreds of feet tall over a residential area. Two city
high schools and a hospital were opened to house the evacuees.
   At least 150 people Saturday and 125 people Friday were treated
at three city hospitals for skin burns and respiratory problems
caused by the fumes, authorities said. There were no reports of
serious injuries.
   ``I don't need this and my kids don't need this,'' said Kathy
Trucx, an evacuee at Municipal Hospital, who said her two children
suffer from bronchitis.
   Authorities said they were abandoning an earlier plan to use 52
tons of neutralizing chemicals after dawn Sunday to try to put out
the blaze at the plant, which makes swimming pool chemicals.
   ``We just decided we can't wait until morning,'' Placanico said.
``It was too dangerous to leave alone.''
   The center of the fire Saturday was a room containing 600 to 800
barrels each filled with 300 pounds of granulated chlorine. The dry
compound is 90 percent chlorine, Placanico said.
   Explosions from the room came ``three and four and six a
minute'' after starting around noon Saturday, said John Higgins,
regional director of the state Department of Environmental Quality
Engineering.
   Higgins said authorities had planned to pump 26 tons each of
boric acid and sodium sulfate through fire hoses into the room
containing the barrels.
   Chlorine is flammable and can burn the skin and lungs. It can be
fatal in large concentrations.
   Around 6 p.m. Saturday, yellow-green clouds rising several
hundred feet were visible from a police and fire command post in a
gas station about two miles from the plant. Shortly afterward, the
command center also was evacuated.
   In some parts of town, visibility was limited to about 50 feet,
witnesses said.
   Some residents in this city of 170,000 were evacuated after the
fire broke out Friday morning and more than 6,000 people were
ordered from their homes Friday night after the fire engulfed three
stories of the brick plant.
   All but about 200 people were allowed to return home Saturday
morning, but when the evacuation area was expanded later in the
day, police with bullhorns herded many of the returnees into school
buses to leave the area.
   ``It smelled like pure bleach was coming through my window and
burning my eyes,'' said Judy Williams, 34, an evacuee at Municipal
Hospital.
   More than a dozen firefighters also were injured, including two
who were knocked against a wall by an exploding barrel around noon
Saturday.
   After Fire Chief Raymond S. Sullivan ordered 35 firefighters to
withdraw from the plant, more barrels could be heard exploding.
Firefighters in the building dove behind trucks.
   The first fire was ignited around 10 a.m. Friday by rain that
blew in an open window and set off highly reactive chlorine pellets
lying in a hopper, Placanico said.
   The first fire was small and quickly extinguished although the
fumes forced the evacuation of about 1,800 people, including 1,200
schoolchildren, he said. However, about 12 hours later, a passing
police officer spotted more flames and fumes.
   The second fire consumed most of one wing of the plant,
orginally a section of the Springfield Arsenal, and forced the
second evacuation.
   State Commissioner of Environmental Quality Engineering Daniel
S. Greenbaum said the old plant was equipped with a sprinkler
system that may have dampened additional barrels of chlorine and
sparked additional reactions and fires.
   State and federal officials will investigate the company's
operations, Greenbaum said.
</TEXT>
