<1ST_LINE>r i BC-Philippines-Capsize     06-19 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Philippines-Capsize,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boat Capsizes and Eight Children Drowned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A motorized canoe filled with
parents and children on a shopping trip for school's opening
capsized, drowning eight of the children, the military said Sunday.
   The boat overturned Saturday after it was buffeted by big waves
brought about by monsoon rains, said Lt. Col. Porcawa Dia, the
Philippine Constabulary commander on Basilan island. The accident
happened between the nearby islands of Bubuan and Saluping in the
Sulu archipelago nearly 600 miles miles south of Manila.
   The boat was carrying about 20 passengers from Bubuan island,
mostly parents and their elementary school children who were on a
last-minute shopping trip for supplies in Basilan for Monday's
school opening.
   Most of the passengers were able to swim back to the overturned
boat and were picked up by passing craft. However, eight of the
children were reported missing and believed to have drowned, Dia
said.
   The capsized craft, called a pumpboat or motorlaunch, is a
motorized canoe with outriggers. In some areas of the Philippines,
pumpboats are the only mode of transportation from one island to
another.
   Many such boats are small and can carry only a few people, but
others can transport up to 100 passengers.
</TEXT>
