<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Iran-Rebels 1stLd-Writethru a0669 06-19 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Iran-Rebels, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0669,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqi-backed Anti-Khomeini Rebels Launch Offensive Into Iran</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Iranian report on fighting,
picks up graf 4 pvs `The rebels...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iraqi-backed rebel army opposed to the
regime of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini said Sunday it launched a
major offensive into western Iran, where it claimed it killed,
wounded, or captured thousands of Iranians.
   The National Liberation Army, an Iraq-based organization of
Iranians opposed to Khomeini's government, said its forces captured
Mehran, an Iranian town on the Iran-Iraq border 100 miles east of
the Iraqi capital of Baghdad. It said its fighters had battled two
divisions of Iranian troops around the town.
   The official Iranian news agency, also monitored in Nicosia on
Sunday, confirmed fighting in the Mehran area. However, it said
fighting in the area pitted Iranian and Iraqi forces.
   One dispatch said a six-pronged attack on Mehran by Iraqi forces
was repulsed and only Iranian mopping-up operations were continuing.
   A second dispatch said clashes between Iranian and Iraqi forces
were intensifying west of Mehran. It said the Iraqis sustained
heavy casualties.
   The Iraq News Agency, quoting Iraq's minister of information,
Latif Nasif Jassim, denied that any Iraqi army troops were involved
in the Mehran offensive. It said all the attackers belonged to the
rebel group and they had captured Mehran.
   The rebels' statement said the offensive was the largest
operation yet undertaken by the rebels. It said the attack involved
22 brigades of combat and support troops and covered a front 31
miles wide.
   The group made its claims in a statement telexed to Nicosia from
Baghdad.
   ``Thousands of enemy troops under Khomeini's command have either
been killed, wounded or captured so far,'' the statement said. It
said strategic heights inside Iran had been captured and two
highways cut.
   The offensive was being led by rebel commander Massoud Rajavi,
the statement said.
   The National Liberation Army, formed a year ago, is built around
activists known as Mujahedeen Khalq, or People's Warriors, who
helped Khomeini overthrow Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlevi in 1979.
However, they were later outlawed by Khomeini's Islamic
fundamentalists.
   They describe themselves as an Islamic movement seeking a
secular government.
   With Iraqi support, the rebel forces have been playing a small
but growing role in the Iran-Iraq war, in its eighth year.
</TEXT>
