<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Indian-Punjab 2ndLd-Writethru a0668 06-19 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Indian-Punjab, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0668,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Least 15 Killed, 30 Injured in Bombing by Suspected Sikh
Extremists</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with death toll revised upward,
attack on farmer in central Punjab; pickup 10th pvs, ``Also Sunday</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected Sikh extremists threw a bomb
Sunday into a crowd watching a Hindu religious series on a
community television, killing at least 15 people and injuring about
30 others, a news agency said.
   The attack was carried out in a market in the town of
Kurukshetra in northern Haryana state, according to the Press Trust
of India news agency. The town is considered holy by Hindus.
   Six of the injured were reported in critical condition at local
hospitals, it said.
   It reported the market was littered with limbs and torn flesh of
the victims.
   The attack came as the crowd and an estimated 100 million
Indians tuned in to state-run television nationwide to watch the
weekly ``Ramayana'' show, which recounts the adventures of the
Hindu god Lord Rama.
   The town of Kurukshetra is holy to Hindus because it was there
that Lord Krishna, an incarnation of one of Hindu's trinity of
gods, gave a lecture on battling for righteousness. His army later
went on to defeat a rival Aryan tribe.
   Sikh extremists have been waging a guerrilla war for an
independent homeland in Punjab since 1982.
   Sikhs, whose religion was founded about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam, claim they are discriminated
against by India's majority Hindus. Sikhs make up less than 2
percent of India's 800 million people but are a majority in Punjab.
   Earlier Sunday, Punjab police said that three policemen were
killed overnight in two separate attacks by Sikh radicals. They
also were blamed for the death Sunday of a Sikh farmer in central
Punjab.
   Also Sunday, Sikh radicals ambushed a car carrying a militant
Hindu leader in Punjab state, killing him, his bodyguard and an
aide, the news agency said.
   The Hindu leader was identified as Rama Kant Jalota, president
of the Punjab Shiv Sena, or army of Shiva. The Shiv Sena views
itself as a defender of Hindus and their religion.
   The news agency said Jalota's car was attacked as he was en
route to Jalandhar, which is a district capital 50 miles southeast
of Amritsar.
   The latest killings raised to more than 1,320 the number of
people killed by the radicals in Punjab since the start of the
year. Last year, 1,030 people died.
   Most of the victims have been Hindus or moderate Sikhs opposed
to the militants' separatist campaign. The radicals have at times
targeted police, government officials and their families.
   Sunday's attack was the second bombing by Sikh extremists
outside Punjab in less than a month.
   On May 20, a series of bombs went off on several buses in
Himachal Pradesh state northeast of Punjab. At least 10 people died.
   The last Sikh attack in Haryana, south of Punjab, came on May 8,
when Sikh extremists attacked a Hindu wedding party. At least 14
people were killed and 26 injured.
</TEXT>
