<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-88 1006EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a BC-ChemicalFire 2ndLd-Writethru a0673 06-19 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Chemical Fire, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0673,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chemical Fire Injures 275, Forces Evacuation of Up to 15,000
Residents</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with fire out, authorities
revising evacuation figure to 10,000 to 15,000 people. Picks up 8th
graf pvs, `The fire engulfed ....' Changes byline.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SP2,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of residents began returning
to their homes early Sunday as firefighters extinguished a chlorine
plant blaze that spread a cloud of toxic gas over two cities,
injuring 275 people.
   The fire, which started Friday, was finally put out Sunday
morning, and fire officials reduced the off-limits zone from 2{
miles to a quarter-mile.
   ``It's the worst public health and environmental disaster in the
past 20 years,'' said John J. Higgins, regional director for the
state Department of Environmental Quality Engineering. The
department took air readings in area churches to see if it was safe
for people to attend Sunday services.
   Authorities Sunday lowered their estimate of the number of
people evacuated from about 30,000 to 10,000 to 15,000. Some of
those returning home Sunday morning had been away for two nights.
   Fumes had stopped forming into the dense cloud of dangerous gas
that had spread throughout the area earlier, said Fire Commissioner
Darnell Williams. Firefighters poured about 14,000 pounds of water
on the blaze every minute during the height of the battle.
   Seven of the 125 firefighters on the line were injured Saturday
night or Sunday morning.
   The old wood and brick building, onetime home of the Springfield
Arsenal, was used by the Advanced Laboratories Co. to make chlorine
products for swimming pools.
   The fire engulfed the two-story, block-long building with
three-story towers, sending flames 100 feet into the air early
Sunday. Officials said a cloud of chlorine fumes about two miles
long blew northeast across the city of 170,000.
   One large room in the building was believed to contain 600 to
800 barrels, each holding about 300 pounds of granulated dry
chlorine, Fire Department spokesman Giorgio Placanico said.
   The fumes went into the adjacent community of Chicopee where
Mayor Joseph Chesney ordered a voluntary evacuation of three
neighborhoods near the city line.
   Fire officials said the Clean Harbors Co. of Kingston, a
hazardous waste firm, brought in a truckload of sodium sulfate, a
neutralizing chemical, early Sunday.
   However, Williams said any use of sodium sulfate or boric acid
would be held up until fire officials are sure they know what was
stored in the big building for fear of creating other problems.
   The city extended an evacuation order to residential
neighborhoods one mile around the plant and 1{ miles to the
northeast.
   Placanico said 20,000 to 30,000 people were evacuated and
several thousand were in four emergency shelters. Others went to
stay with friends or relatives, or waited in unaffected areas of
the city in hopes the cloud would disperse soon.
   Two elderly residents declined to leave their homes and were
brought out by police, said James Controvich, city emergency
response coordinator. State troopers came in to help guard affected
areas, but there had been no problems with looters.
   Officials said 150 people were treated at three city hospitals
Saturday, while 125 had been treated on Friday for skin burns and
respiratory problems caused by the corrosive chlorine fumes. No
serious injuries were reported.
   Chlorine is flammable and can burn the skin and lungs. It can be
fatal in large concentrations. Firefighters could get no closer
than 100 feet from the building, even with protective gear.
   Some residents had been evacuated after the fire broke out
Friday morning, but most were allowed to return home later.
   However, more than 6,000 people were ordered from their homes
Friday night after the rekindled fire engulfed a wing of the
four-story brick and wood plant.
   Two city high schools, a hospital and the Springfield Civic
Center were opened to house the evacuees.
</TEXT>
