<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-88 1145EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drought-WaterQuality Bjt   06-19 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Water Quality, Bjt,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Falling Water Level May Raise Pollution Danger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drought staggering America's farmlands may
pose a danger for the rest of the nation, too _ increased pollution
in the rivers, lakes and wells that provide drinking water and
recreation.
   Millions of streams and rivers across the nation carry off
sewage, industrial wastes, agricultural chemicals and other
pollutants. Some people describe the process with the rhyme: ``The
solution to pollution is dilution.''
   ``Just common sense would tell you that if you have less flow in
a stream, there is less dilution of whatever components are being
carried by that stream,'' pointed out Ben Jones, assistant regional
hydrologist for the U.S. Geological Survey in Menlo Park, Calif.
   There have, for example, been recent complaints from Northern
California that large volumes of sewage discharge had appeared in
streams.
   These were streams where there was normally enough water to
handle the treated sewage, Jones said. But because of dry
conditions, suddenly the volume of sewage exceeded that of clean
water and people reacted to the sudden change.
   Drought-induced low water in the Mississippi and Ohio rivers has
attracted attention by stranding barges, but it also has
concentrated pollutants in those rivers, which accept the runoff
from much of the nation.
   Bob Meade of the Geological Survey's Denver office has just
returned from a water-quality survey of the Mississippi. One of the
things the scientists found was a broken sewer in Memphis, spewing
thousands of gallons of what he termed ``floatable solids'' into
the river.
   Meade's detailed pollution measurements won't be completed for
months, but he concurred with Jones that reduced river flows
increase the concentrations of chemicals like nitrates and
herbicides that are dissolved in the water.
   Warm weather and low water levels lead to stress on much aquatic
life, added Gary Pederson, a survey hydrologist in Atlanta.
   For one thing, warmer water can hold less dissolved oxygen,
Pederson explained. That, in itself, can be a problem for fish and
other aquatic life. Moreover, because oxygen is needed to help
clean the water, low water and less oxygen increases the chances of
the water becoming toxic.
   The survey's monthly analysis of the nation's streams and rivers
showed flows at below normal in May in the Pacific Northwest,
California, the Great Plains and the Southeast.
   The Mississippi marked its second lowest flow in 60 years while
the St. Lawrence, the nation's second largest river, fell below
normal for the first time since 1967.
   May saw five record low stream flows recorded at locations in
Florida, Alabama, North Carolina and Arkansas, the survey reported.
   In addition to lakes and rivers, known as surface water,
millions of Americans depend on ground water: those great
underground pools tapped by wells.
   ``As a drought deepens and strengthens, people tend to go more
and more to ground water supplies as a source,'' Jones added. And
in some cases they may start to pump water from underground
aquifers which are not normally used.
   Ground water is already more concentrated with minerals because
of its longer contact with them, he noted. ``As water supplies
become less and less available for agriculture, there will be more
and more chance of arid areas having soil begin to salt up from
water with a higher mineral content,'' he said.
   Salt-laden soil already has been reported as a problem in some
parts of the Southwest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880619-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-88 1150EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-South Bjt   06-19 0951</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-South, Bjt,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Southern Democratiic Leaders Pull Together To Back Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louise Lindblom surveyed the crowd that
turned out for Michael Dukakis. ``People who've worked in every
campaign in Alabama since 1960 _ they showed up this afternoon,''
she said.
   She pointed out Billy Joe Camp who was a leading backer of
George C. Wallace and a minister who was Alabama chairman for
George McGovern in 1972.
   ``I've never seen them all together at one time,'' said
Lindblom, a veteran of state and national Democratic Party politics.
   It was a remarkable turnout in a state the Massachusetts
governor had little reason to think he could carry against
Republican George Bush in the fall presidential election.
   The Democratic presidential candidate carried Alabama only once
in the last six elections.
   A three-day trip through seven Southern states that his staff
described as the first swing of the general election campaign was
marked by the turnout of Democratic Party officials, people who
often had kept their distance from their party's presidential
nominees in recent elections.
   ``Folks who hid out before, they ain't hiding out on Mike
Dukakis,'' said Larry Harrington, an aide to Tennessee Sen. Albert
Gore Jr.
   Gore endorsed Dukakis on this trip and so did Gov. Ray Maybus of
Mississippi and both talked about their willingness to campaign for
the Massachusetts governor.
   Equally significant, if not more so, was the willingness of
party officials and members of Congress to come out and be seen in
public with the Massachusetts politician who has locked up their
party's presidential nomination. The victory of a man perceived
early on as a Northern liberal was an outcome they had hoped to
avoid when they banded together to get nearly all Southern states
to hold primaries on March 8, an effort designed to give one of
their own a shot at the nomination.
   But Dukakis has shaken that label and the Southerners appeared
comfortable with him, far more comfortable than they ever were with
Walter Mondale in 1984.
   ``Everybody committed to help us put together the coalition we
need to win in the fall,'' said Donna Brazile, deputy political
director of the campaign.
   ``Will you help us?'' she said the politicians were asked during
private meetings at every stop. ``They said yes.''
   ``It was a good three days,'' Dukakis said as he flew back to
Boston.
   The Southern trip was a statement by Dukakis, a challenge to
Bush on what the vice president thought was his own turf, his
political base.
   ``I wanted so very much to make this first swing of the campaign
in the South,'' Dukakis told the rally in the Alabama capital.
   He said he wanted to demonstrate that ``I'm serious and you're
serious about campaigning hard in the South, working hard in the
South and winning the South.''
   He offered Southern voters the kind of tough talk about crime
and drugs that they want to hear and showed no sign of being
rattled by the Republican surrogates who preceded him at many stops
and branded him a ``Teddy Kennedy liberal'' from Massachusetts who
was soft on crime.
   Dukakis pointed to statistics that showed his state has the
lowest homicide rate of any industrial state and also had one of
the largest drops in major crime.
   The Massachusetts governor dismissed criticism from one such
surrogate, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, as the words of someone who
``doesn't know beans from brown bread.''
   When Bush attacked Dukakis for a program under which criminals
are permitted brief furloughs from prisons, even convicted
murderers, the Dukakis' staff was quick to point out that
California had a similar program under Gov. Ronald Reagan.
   Opinion polls certainly had a role in encouraging Southern
Democratic politicians to stand by their certain nominee.
   The day Dukakis arrived in the region a new survey by
Atlanta-based pollster Clairborne Darden of voters in nine states
in the region said Dukakis was leading Bush by a narrow margin of
45 percent to 42 percent, within the poll's 3 percent margin of
error.
   But those politicians knew better than to put much faith in
polls at this stage of a campaign.
   They also knew that most of their states have been regularly
supporting Republican presidential candidates for two decades with
the exception of 1976 when Georgian Jimmy Carter was the Democratic
nominee.
   A lot of things can change the campaign mood in the months
before Election Day.
   Dukakis still must deal with Jesse Jackson, find common ground
on issues without seeming to cave in to the former civil rights
activist, resist demands without alienating black voters who are an
indispensable part of the Democratic coalition.
   ``There's a lot of indecision among blacks,'' said Brazile, who
worked with Jackson in his 1984 presidential campaign.
   ``People don't know who Mike Dukakis is,'' she said. ``All they
know about Mike Dukakis is he was Jesse Jackson's competitor and
he's a Democrat and a good Democrat.''
   B.A. McDowell, a doctor from Bessemer, stood at the back of the
crowd and listened to Dukakis.
   A Jackson supporter in the Alabama primary, McDowell said he
thought Dukakis needed help in the South, the kind of help he'd get
from a Southern running mate, somebody like Gore or Sen. Sam Nunn
of Georgia.
   ``The general consensus, I think, in the black community is
Jesse ought to be offered it (the vice presidential nomination),''
McDowell said. ``But the politicians who know how things work say
if Jackson is on the ticket he's going to run all the white folks
off.''
   Was McDowell impressed with Dukakis?
   ``I think he's all right,'' he said. ``He's the closest thing
we've got to a winner.''
</TEXT>
