<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Leahy-ThurmondFeud Bjt   06-19 0797</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Leahy-Thurmond Feud, Bjt,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators' Feud on Judgeship Nominations Hits Boiling Point</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sens. Patrick J. Leahy and Strom Thurmond have
been locked in a partisan snit for months over the pace of
judgeship confirmations, and last week, the feud just about reached
the boiling point.
   The two met privately, senator-to-senator, in an anteroom
outside a committee room as staffers outside the door could hear _
as one described it _ ``the decibel level rise.''
   The trouble began in the opening moments of a hearing for a
judicial nominee from California, when Thurmond, R-S.C., asked that
testimony get under way.
   Leahy, a liberal Democrat from Vermont, who was presiding, chose
instead to read his entire single-spaced, 10-page letter to
Thurmond, denying that Democrats were stalling President Reagan's
court nominees.
   It wasn't long before Leahy's cigar smoke wafted toward
Thurmond, whose disdain for smoking is equaled only by his low
regard for alcohol and liberals. Thurmond kept waving papers to
deflect the thickening smoke.
   Later, when Thurmond asked witnesses opposing the nominee if
they belonged to gay or lesbian groups, Leahy accused his rival of
McCarthyism.
   Then, as the hearing ended, Leahy cleared the area of staffers,
and the blunt-speaking former prosecutor from Vermont and the
85-year-old former judge from South Carolina had their meeting.
   ``Sometimes you need conversations that are senator to
senator,'' Leahy said.
   But, lucky for Leahy, Thurmond didn't resort to the method of
resolving disputes that he used more than 20 years ago.
   In that instance, Thurmond's opponent was former liberal
Democratic Sen. Ralph Yarborough of Texas. And instead of moving
behind closed doors, the two senators, both 61 at the time,
wrestled on the floor outside a Senate Commerce Committee room. The
issue was Thurmond's attempt to stall a vote on a director for a
civil rights panel.
   Still, according to reports at the time, the battle that July
day in 1964 ``was good tempered,'' with ``no sharp words exchanged
before or after.''
   The feud between Thurmond and Leahy, on the other hand, has
become a very personal affair, especially to Leahy, who accused
Thurmond of hounding him to speed up confirmation hearings even
while Leahy's son was hospitalized for surgery.
   Thurmond, for his part, denied that there's anything personal
involved. ``I feel sorry his son was hospitalized,'' he said,
adding he has an obligation as ranking GOP committee member to
represent Republicans who believe their court nominees are victims
of a Democratic stall.
   Leahy countered that most nominees are moving ahead in timely
fashion, but blamed any delays on his party's refusal to rubber
stamp the president's candidates, and on Justice Department delays
in responding to committee information requests.
   To complicate matters, Judiciary Committee Chairman Joseph R.
Biden Jr., D-Del., has been recuperating at home from two aneurysm
operations, and is unable to act as a peacemaker.
   When Republicans controlled the Senate and Thurmond was
Judiciary Committee chairman from 1981-86, Biden developed a
special relationship with the South Carolina lawmaker. The two like
each other personally, keep the level of animosity low when they
disagree, and often work out compromise legislation on key issues.
   While Leahy has handled confirmation hearings for the committee,
Biden has been heavily involved in judgeship issues. He has
promised that every nominee would receive a fair hearing and a
vote. He likely would have tried to defuse the Leahy-Thurmond
battle.
   Leahy said in an interview that GOP senators who sponsored
nominees _ and the candidates themselves _ have been complimentary
on the fairness of their hearings.
   ``I told Thurmond I can't understand what his motives are in
constantly raising questions of delay, when other senators don't
see that at all,'' Leahy said. ``I said all the people who Biden
promised will get votes will (get them).
   ``I asked why he raised questions which he keeps asking over and
over again. He even did so in a week when I had a son in for
serious surgery. I didn't find his answers satisfactory.''
   Thurmond, in an interview, said he told Leahy ``There's been
delay after delay. I said Biden promised to have these judges acted
on, and he (Leahy) was not following that course.''
   One Democratic source, knowledgeable about the feud, said, ``I
don't think there's any way to control what two senators do in the
absence of the chairman.
   ``There's no doubt Thurmond would be going to Biden and trying
to work out something. But to say Biden could have kept this from
hard feelings, is an overstatement.''
   Thurmond has shown an ability to behave as a true Southern
gentleman.
   And Thurmond decided to play the gentleman last week, when asked
if he resented Leahy sending cigar smoke his way.
   ``The wind was blowing that way,'' he said.
</TEXT>
