<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Tatars     06-19 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Tatars,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Tatars Reportedly Detained</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dissident said Sunday that police detained five
people who planned to protest in Moscow for return of the Crimean
Tatars' homeland, taken away by Josef Stalin.
   Alexander Podrabinek said four Crimean Tatars were detained
Sunday morning for alleged violation of internal passport laws.
Podrabinek, editor of the weekly dissident journal
Express-Khronika, said a fifth man was arrested Saturday.
   He said those detained Sunday included a Muscovite, Yevgeny
Ametov, and three Tatars from the Krasnodar area of southern
Russia. He did not identify them.
   Podrabinek said the man detained Saturday was Reshat Zhemilev of
Tashkent in Soviet Uzbekistan.
   Ametov and the three Tatars from Krasnodar had planned to
present a petition at Communist Party Central Committee
headquarters Monday demanding that a party conference that opens
June 28 consider returning their homeland to them.
   Podrabinek said about 50 police and plainclothes agents detained
them near a monument to Russian writer Nikolai Gogol, where they
were meeting with Moscow residents to explain their demands.
   The three had arrived from Krasnodar on Saturday, he said.
   Soviets may be in a location other than their home for 72 hours
without registering with authorities.
   Another dissident, Valery Senderov, said Zhemilev had been in
Moscow for several weeks before being detained on a street
Saturday. He said he had no other information about the arrest.
   Crimean Tatars, descendants of the Mongols, were exiled from
their homeland by Stalin for allegedly collaborating with Nazi
invaders in World War II. Many died on their way to regions of the
Ural Mountains and Soviet Central Asia.
   Hundreds of Tatars converged on Moscow last summer, and in late
July they staged an overnight protest in Red Square.
   The Soviet government formed a commission under President Andrei
A. Gromyko to study their demands and then forcibly removed them
from Moscow several weeks later when they refused to go home.
</TEXT>
