<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CyprusTalks     06-19 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cyprus Talks,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cyprus President Agrees to Talks with Turkish Cypriot Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President George Vassiliou has agreed to
meet with the leader of this Mediterranean island's breakaway
Turkish state to discuss reunification, an official announcement
said Sunday.
   Vassiliou agreed Saturday to a proposal by U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar to hold talks with Rauf
Denktash, the government announcement said.
   In a recent report to the U.N. Security Council, Perez de
Cuellar said he had proposed to Vassiliou and Denktash that they
meet soon without preconditions to seek a settlement based on a
two-state federation.
   The announcement said Vassiliou ``decided to respond positively
and accept the U.N. secretary-general's proposals as they stand.''
   A Greek Cypriot official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the talks may start in July in Geneva during a scheduled visit
there by Perez de Cuellar.
   Turkish Cypriot officials have indicated Denktash would accept
the secretary-general's proposal and meet with Vassiliou, but no
official announcement has been made.
   Cyprus has been divided since Turkish troops invaded in 1974 and
captured the northern third of the island after a Greek Cypriot
coup aimed at uniting the island with Greece.
   Turkish Cypriots, who comprise one-fifth of the island's 650,000
people, have formed their own breakaway state, headed by Denktash,
in the Turkish-controlled territory.
   Several rounds of talks between Turkish and Greek Cypriot
leaders, under U.N. mediation, have failed to resolve disputes over
the form of a federation and withdrawal of about 29,000 Turkish
troops stationed on northern Cyprus.
</TEXT>
