<DOCNO> AP880619-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-88 1205EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Nunn-Drugs     06-19 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nunn-Drugs,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nunn Says Enlisting Military Not Sole Answer To Drug War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee has a simple response to those who insist the war against
illegal drugs can be won with legislation requiring the military to
seal U.S. borders against narcotics traffickers.
   ``If you passed it, it would be like passing a law saying it
shall rain two inches in the Midwest by Sunday morning,'' said Sen.
Sam Nunn, D-Ga. ``You can pass it and it makes you feel good but
it's not going to do anything.''
   The House, however, passed such legislation just last month as
part of its defense budget bill for fiscal year 1989. The Senate
also included an anti-drug provision in its version of the defense
bill, although it did not go nearly as far as the House.
   The Senate bill would give the military a greater role in the
detection and tracking of drug smugglers, would allow the use of
military equipment and personnel in border enforcement and would
give the Navy limited arrest powers outside U.S. waters.
   Nunn, who persuaded the Senate two years ago to reject a similar
House proposal to use the military to seal the borders against drug
traffickers, helped fashion the compromise amendment the Senate
attached to its defense bill.
   But in an interview last week, Nunn said he's still not
convinced Congress should extend arrest powers to the military. He
described his involvement in the development of the Senate drug
interdiction plan as ``an effort to make some sense out of the bill
that was inevitably going to pass.
   ``You sort of sense the mood of a body and something was going
to pass,'' he said. ``The Senate of the United States was going to
shake its fist and say to the people of the country, we have dealt
with the drug problem, we have sicked the military on them.''
   Nunn said the chorus of election-year calls in Congress for
greater military involvement in the anti-drug effort is just
another example of the propensity on Capitol Hill for proposing
easy answers to complex problems.
   ``There is no easy answer,'' he said. ``This is a deep societal
problem and we have to treat it in a multifaceted way, with
education, and with health preventive measures and also with law
enforcement and interdiction.
   ``If you get all the effort on interdiction, and you don't do
anything about cutting down the demand side, the drug user is going
to find some way to get drugs in here,'' he said.
   Since both houses approved their anti-drug amendments to the
defense bill during floor debate, bypassing the normal committee
process, Nunn took the unusual step two weeks ago of scheduling
hearings by his committee on an issue that already had been acted
on.
   The message from most witnesses at those hearings was strikingly
similar to what Nunn has been preaching: that past drug
interdiction efforts haven't been effective in slowing the flow of
drugs into the country and that anti-drug efforts should be focused
more on curbing demand.
   ``The most you can do with interdiction is make the price
higher,'' Nunn said. ``And making the price higher is a worthy goal
because it cuts down consumption. But making the price higher
doesn't solve the problem.''
   Nunn, who now is heading the House-Senate conference on the
defense bill, said he hopes the panel will not decide on a major
increase in drug intediction efforts by the military.
   The House proposal to seal the borders, he said, would cost $3
billion to $5 billion and likely would do little more than force
the drug smugglers to shift their operations.
   Ideally, Nunn said, the military's role in the drug war should
be limited to gathering intelligence on the source of illegal
drugs, conducting surveillance of ships and planes suspected of
carrying drugs and communicating that information to civilian law
enforcement authorities.
   If the military carries out those three tasks effectively, he
said, then domestic law enforcement agencies should be able to
handle the arrests of drug traffickers without any help from the
military, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880619-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-88 1210EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CigaretteSuit     06-19 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cigarette Suit,0642</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mixed Cigarette Suit Verdict Bolsters Views Of Both Sides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The landmark Cipollone cigarette liability
case boiled down to a few key questions, not all of which got
definitive answers.
   The question asked by the cigarette makers was, should a company
really be forced to pay money because a smoker contracted lung
cancer when she knew people were saying cigarettes were dangerous?
   Attorneys for Rose Cipollone, who died in 1984 at 58 after four
decades of smoking, put it another way: shouldn't the makers of her
cigarettes _ just like any other company _ be held responsible for
their actions in making a potentially dangerous product?
   And the 4{-month trial, which ended a week ago Monday with the
nation's first liability finding against the industry, posed a
broader question: Is the courtroom the place to change public
policy?
   The jury cleared Liggett Group Inc., Lorillard Inc. and Philip
Morris Inc. of conspiring to misrepresent the dangers of smoking.
   But it granted $400,000 to Antonio Cipollone in finding that
Liggett, which made the cigarettes his wife smoked before warning
labels were put on packs in 1966, violated advertising promises
that its products were safe.
   The jury also partly found against Liggett on a failure-to-warn
claim, determining the company should have told consumers of
smoking's risks before 1966, that the omission contributed to Mrs.
Cipollone's smoking and that the smoking contributed to her death.
   Yet the panel said Mrs. Cipollone was mostly responsible for her
injuries and thus not entitled to damages.
   Aside from the industry's exoneration on the fraud conspiracy
claim, company lawyers said they essentially won the case because
the jury found Mrs. Cipollone responsible for her injuries,
supporting the classic industry argument that smokers make an
independent, intelligent choice to smoke.
   But Cipollone's lawyers said the verdict supported the charge
that smoking causes cancer _ which the industry denies has been
proven _ and that actions by a cigarette maker can be blamed for a
smoker's disease.
   Industry victory proclamations caused some skepticism in
anti-smoking ranks.
   ``To me, it seems like the captain of the Titanic saying, `Just
a little ice, folks,''' said Don Davis, an Austin, Texas, attorney
whose firm handles cigarette liability cases.
   Both sides promised an appeal. They have until June 29 to file
post-trial motions with U.S. District Judge H. Lee Sarokin, with
oral arguments expected toward the end of July.
   Anti-smoking advocates see liability cases as a way of reducing
the number of smokers, raising the price of cigarettes through
mounting industry legal bills and drumming up public opinion
against cigarettes. But others don't see that as the role of the
courts.
   A jury ``rules in favor of a plaintiff or defendant, but doesn't
rule on the issue involved,'' said Boris Yavitz, a Columbia
University business school professor with a chair in business
ethics.
   Consensus on rules of a society should be reached first through
public debate and the actions of elected officials, and the courts
should then enforce compliance with what is decided, in Yavitz'
view.
   But the courts have often been put to good use for important
causes, said John F. Banzhaf, a George Washington University law
professor and anti-smoking activist.
   Environmental protection and rights for minorities, prisoners
and women have been won and maintained in courtrooms, he said.
   Cigarette liability trials, with an individual victim and
testimony from bereaved family members, take the impersonal face
away from statistics about smoking's casualties, he adds.
   A momentous verdict, like in the Cipollone case, grabs the
attention of legislators. And an anti-industry verdict will spawn
more filings, spreading the industry's legal resources thin and
creating more opportunity for errors by industry lawyers, Banzhaf
contended.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880619-0034 </DOCNO>
