<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SkinHeadAbduction     06-19 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Skin Head Abduction,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Girl And Her Boa Constrictor Said Abducted by Women With Shaved
Heads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mounties, a boa constrictor and five women
with shaved heads, at least one with a tattoo on her scalp, rode
out a drama over the weekend that ranged across Oregon and
Washington and ended up in a British Columbia jail.
   It began Friday night, police said, when the five abducted a
16-year-old girl from a party in Portland, Ore., forcing her into
her own car. The girl was tied up, beaten repeatedly and threatened
before being pushed out on Interstate 5 about 50 miles north of
Seattle.
   The women drove off with the car and the girl's pet boa
constrictor, police said.
   The teen-ager, thrown into a ditch and still tied up, managed to
crawl to the edge of the highway, where she was discovered by a
passer-by and taken to the hospital, said Elliott Woodall,
spokesman for the Snohomish County sheriff's department. She was
treated for multiple bruises and released to her mother Saturday
afternoon, a nursing supervisor said.
   Late Saturday, the car was spotted speeding by the Royal
Canadian Mounted Police in Golden, British Columbia, about 200
miles north of the U.S. border. Officers stopped it, discovered it
was stolen and arrested the three women inside. The whereabouts of
the other two suspects were not known.
   The snake was recovered unharmed and was being looked after by
the mounties, Woodall said.
   A woman described by the victim as having an English accent and
a tattoo on the back of her shaved head that read, ``East Side
Chelseas,'' was among those arrested, he said. Canadian authorities
said she was a Calgary, Alberta, resident and that the other two
women taken into custody were U.S. residents whose addresses were
not immediately known.
   Robbery was the apparent motive for the abduction and attack,
Woodall said.
</TEXT>
