<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-88 1218EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Notebook Bjt   06-19 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Notebook, Bjt,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Graffiti, Beaver and Exotic Dances Greet Summit Delegates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Under the slogan ``Let Toronto Shine,'' civic
leaders and summit organizers launched a clean-up campaign of what
is already one of the cleanest cities of North America.
   But some of their efforts backfired.
   Faster than crews of industrious workmen could spray and scrape
graffiti off some 200 buildings, groups of university vigilantes
were spray-painting the surfaces with fresh wall writings.
   ``Cancel the Summit, Cancel the Clean-Up,'' read one gaudily
painted protest in northeast Toronto, the work of a political
science major at the University of Toronto.
   ``This city has more graffiti now than ever before _ not that
they had very much at all,'' said the student, who would only
identify himself as John. ``If they hadn't called attention to this
with their clean-up, no one would have noticed this graffiti.''
   But the rest of the $48,000 summit spruce-up was received with
approval by local residents.
   Enterprising residents took advantage of a clean-up hotline set
up by the city to rid their yards and basements of debris. All they
had to do was call the hot line and complain of an unseemly blemish
on the summit landscape, such as left-over cement or a garbage heap
in their front yard, and a clean-up crew would show up and cart
away the offending items _ gratis.
   ``Many people just used the opportunity to get rid of things
they didn't want. People figured it's free, why not?'' said Carlo
Deriva, a taxi driver who took advantage of the service.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   One of the most eager summit participants is Amik, a
two-year-old beaver who has drawn more media attention than most
heads of state.
   The reason: he is on display in Summit Square, an enclosed area
where officials from the eight summit delegations and the estimated
3,000 journalists covering the events can eat and drink for free.
   By day, Amik swims around in a small pool, munching contently on
carrots and corn. At night, he checks into a luxury hotel for a
long soak in the tub of his handler, Julie Perreten.
   ``He's never been away on his own and he would have been very
stressed without me,'' she said. The home of the 30-pound mammal is
at the Science Center in Sudbury, Ontario, about 300 miles north of
here.
   ``He loves it here. He's getting a lot of attention,'' she added.
   The beaver, Canada's national animal, reaches maturity at the
age of 4. Amik will grow to weigh about 60 pounds, said Miss
Perreten.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   For those summit leaders who get bored poring over briefing
papers at night, a Toronto strip joint is offering an alternative:
a free performance by exotic dancers.
   ``If they can prove they're a head of state, they get a free
table and a girl to dance on it,'' said Ted Cody, who works at the
club called Filmore's.
   Filmore's is next door to the headquarters of the joint summit
security task force. ``The neighborhood is crawling with police,''
Cody said, ``and it's not even a raid.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A local drug store chain also is cashing in on the summit, which
city leaders hope will enhance Toronto's chances to host the 1996
Summer Olympics and the year 2000's World Fair.
   ``Who would you rather follow home this week? Maggie, Francois,
Helmut or Nobi,'' the radio commercial says.
   Shoppers can sign up to win a free trip to the country of
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, French President Francois
Mitterrand, German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, or even to the far off
Land of the Rising Sun, whose leader, Noboru Takeshita, is one of
the seven summit leaders.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The local media is giving the summit maximum exposure.
   The Toronto Sun, a tabloid, has featured a skimpily clad woman
on its third page every day for the past week. Each woman was
photographed waving the flag of one of the summit countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
