<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-88 1222EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Media Bjt   06-19 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Media, Bjt,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands of Journalists Gather for `Non-Event'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of journalists brushed up on
international economics, pored over the words of world leaders and
searched Sunday for a new angle on what has become an old story _
the annual economic summit of industrialized democracies.
   ``With the possible exception of royal visits, economic summits
are the most over-covered non-events on the media calendar,'' wrote
columnist Jeffrey Simpson in the Toronto Globe and Mail.
   Bob Asman, executive producer of NBC News, said the summits
``have become so institutionalized'' that they tend ``to be routine
and routine things aren't news.''
   Moreover, this year's gathering is expected to be low key.
   President Reagan, one of the seven world leaders at the meeting,
is a lame-duck with only seven months remaining in his term.
   In addition, the world economy is showing few trouble signs.
   Only a possible dispute over the unglamorous question of
agricultural subsidies threatens to mar the event. The United
States has proposed eliminating all agricultural subsidies by the
year 2000, a suggestion that has raised the ire of Europeans whose
farmers are heavily subsidized.
   Yet, summit organizers say nearly 3,000 reporters, editors,
technicians, producers, cameramen and others falling into the
``media'' category have been accredited to the gathering.
   Canadian reporters keeping tabs on their country's performance
as host of the 14th meeting account for about half the media crowd,
according to summit spokeswoman Joan Walters.
   The United States has sent about 400 journalists, and Japan, 212.
   In all, some four-dozen countries are represented by journalists
working at computer terminals, typewriters and sound booths
spanning the length of 2{ football fields in the Metropolitan
Toronto Convention Center.
   Why the media crush?
   ``We expect the amount of real hard news to be minimal but you
never can tell,'' said Asman. ``When the leaders of the Free World
nations gather, you must be prepared to cover.''
   Jeff Goldman, associate producer of PBS' MacNeil-Lehrer News
Hour, agreed, saying, ``You can't ignore it, certainly.''
   But does he expect much news from the event? ``I don't think
so,'' he replied, laughing. ``I think it's going to be more
ceremonial than substantive this time.''
   But for Susan Zirinsky, senior producer for CBS News and a
veteran of about a half-dozen summits, the gatherings are never
boring.
   ``They take on a life of their own. ... It's the nature of the
beast,'' she said. ``I don't think I've ever been to a summit that
I can say was dull. There's always something,'' she said.
   But some news organizations have scaled down their coverage
compared to past gatherings, which rotate among the United States,
France, Italy, Japan, Canada, Great Britain and Germany.
   ``The size of the effort here is smaller than it has been in
other summits,'' said Michael G. Duffy, senior producer for special
events of ABC News.
   Coverage has been reduced, he said, because of the limited
amount of news expected from the summit.
   Moreover, he noted, it comes just weeks after the U.S.-Soviet
summit in Moscow, which attracted about 5,000 journalists.
   Unlike the Moscow summit, none of the principal anchormen for
the major U.S. television evening newscasts plans to broadcast his
program from Toronto.
   The networks will carry coverage of the summit in their news
programs but not to the extent of the historic meeting between
Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev. That reunion prompted
widespread coverage of the Soviet Union, a country still seen as a
threat and an enigma by many Americans.
   Duffy said the more limited coverage of the Toronto gathering
gives news organizations ``an opportunity to cover the economic
summit a little more economically.''
   Ms. Zirinsky described CBS' effort as ``money conscious.''
   Japanese journalists, though, appear to be pulling out all the
stops.
   Hidetoshi Fujisawa, a Washington correspondent for the leading
Japanese TV network NHK, described their reporting as ``very, very
heavy ... maybe the biggest coverage among broadcasters.''
   Japanese viewers, he said, are interested in learning how their
country is perceived by the other leaders because of criticism in
recent years of the nation's enormous trade surplus.
   ``How Japan is seen in this summit,'' he said, ``is very, very
important.''
   ``We cover much heavier than the United States ... because we
have the hours to cover (and) Japanese people are very interested
in international affairs,'' he said.
   But to Simpson, whose column ran in Saturday's editions of the
Globe and Mail, ``Summits represent the classic manifestation of a
sensible idea gone wild. ... Put simply, the media attention stands
in inverse relation to the event's importance.''
  
</TEXT>
