<1ST_LINE>u i AM-India-Violence Bjt   06-19 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Violence, Bjt,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bombing Kills 15, Wounds 25 In Haryana State</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARBAKSH SINGH NANDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KURUKSHETRA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb planted by Sikh extremists
exploded Sunday in a crowd of people gathered outside an
electronics shop to watch a popular Hindu epic on television,
police said. Fifteen people died and 25 were wounded.
   The bomb was hidden in a cloth bag and left among the mainly
poor Hindu laborers who were watching the program. Officers said
the bomb apparently was detonated by remote control.
   Shortly after the bombing in Kurukshetra in Haryana state, Sikh
radicals assassinated the head of a militant Hindu group in
neighboring Punjab state. The Hindu leader's bodyguard and an aide
also were killed.
   In other violence in Punjab, Sikh extremists shot and killed
three police officers late Saturday, police said. They also were
blamed for the death Sunday of a Sikh farmer in central Punjab.
   A full alert was ordered in six states and in New Delhi, India's
capital.
   The bomb exploded a few minutes after the start of ``Ramayana,''
a popular weekly television serial. The story recounts adventures
of the Hindu god Lord Rama, and some radical Sikhs had warned
people not to watch it.
   Sikhs are a religious minority in India and claim discrimination
by the majority Hindus.
   ``I had come to the market to buy food and then I realized it
was time for `Ramayana,''' said Ram Pal, a 42-year-old civil
servant, from his hospital bed.
   ``I stopped outside the television shop. Suddenly there was an
explosion. I was hurled off my feet,'' said Pal, whose left arm was
cut by shrapnel.
   The blast shattered glass cases inside the shop and started a
stampede among the 150 people near the store.
   Blood and pieces of bodies covered the lane outside the shop.
   Police said bodies of 11 people could not be identified. Four
others died on their way to a hospital.
   Police blamed the bombing on Sikh extremists. They said the
explosive was left outside the shop.
   Authorities closed roads around the city of 500,000, about 90
miles north of New Delhi, but reported no arrests.
   It was the second bombing attack by Sikh extremists outside
Punjab in less than a month.
   On May 20, a series of bombs exploded in several buses in
Himachal Pradesh state. At least 10 people died.
   In Punjab, Rama Kant Jalota, president of a group to protect
Hindus and their religion, was assassinated by Sikh radicals who
overtook his car on a highway and opened fire, police said.
   Jalota's bodyguard and an accountant in the group also were
killed, the police said. Another bodyguard was reported in serious
condition and two bystanders were injured, police said.
   There were no details on the other slayings in Punjab.
   Hindu militants called for a general strike Monday in Punjab to
protest the slayings.
   The killings raised to more than 1,325 the number of people
killed in Punjab by Sikh extremists since Jan. 1. Militants have
been blamed for at least 42 more deaths in adjoining Himachal
Pradesh and Haryana states.
   The Sikh extremists have been waging a guerrilla war for an
independent homeland in Punjab since 1982.
   Sikhs' religion was founded about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam.
   Most of the extremists' victims have been Hindus or moderate
Sikhs opposed to the separatist campaign.
   Sikhs make up less than 2 percent of India's 800 million people
but are a majority in Punjab.
</TEXT>
