<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-88 1253EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Wright-Ethics Bjt   06-19 1132</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wright-Ethics, Bjt,1,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Politics, Capitol Hill Ill Will Work Against House Speaker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A combination of national politics and Capitol
Hill ill will ensures that House Speaker Jim Wright won't soon
shake the ethics allegations against him even if he proves his
claim that he violated no rules.
   Wright wants the House ethics committee, which announced it is
examining six possible violations of House rules by the Texas
Democrat, to quickly dispose of the case.
   But the committee is under pressure from Republicans to hire
outside counsel _ even though it is the only panel in the House
where Republicans hold the same number of votes as Democrats.
   Sources familiar with the panel's thinking say the case against
Wright is not considered strong, but members are determined to
avoid charges of a ``whitewash.'' If an outside counsel is brought
in, the earliest a finding could be made would be September, said
one source, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   Even without an outside counsel, at the minimum, Wright will
remain under a cloud until after the Democratic National Convention
next month in Atlanta, where Wright is scheduled to serve as
chairman.
   And many Republicans have made it clear they won't accept a
finding of ``innocent'' if it comes, because it was the Democrats
who wrote the current House rules and the loopholes that Wright has
taken advantage of.
   ``Power corrupts, in my estimation, and they (the Democrats) are
corrupt,'' said Rep. Barbara Vucanovich, R-Nev., chairman of the
Republican Study Committee, a group of House conservatives that
this week called for an outside counsel.
   Although Wright might proclaim he didn't violate any rules, she
said, ``if he doesn't think it's unethical, I think he needs a
course in ethics.''
   ``I don't think this blows over until after the (November)
general election,'' said Rep. Beryl Anthony, D-Ark., citing the GOP
need to use Wright to counter the charges of sleaze against the
Reagan administration.
   House Democrats have long made hay of the administration's
ethical lapses, with the House civil service subcommittee compiling
a list of 242 officials implicated through March 30. Some have been
cleared, but many have been convicted or resigned.
   As a result, Republicans need to smear Wright as much as
possible, Anthony said. ``Outside of nailing the speaker's hide on
the wall, they're not going to be satisfied with anything,'' he
said.
   However, there is division among Republican ranks over how far
that campaign should go.
   Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., whose complaint launched the ethics
probe against the speaker, and others of the far right wing of the
party have included attacks on the backgrounds of some of Wright's
employees.
   The speaker's top legislative aide, John Mack, served two years
in prison after pleading guilty 15 years ago to malicious wounding.
Wright hired Mack, now 34, as a clerk at the urging of the
speaker's daughter, after Mack was put on a work release program.
Mack is Wright's daughter's brother-in-law.
   Also named in the attacks by Republicans was a press aide and
speech writer for Wright, George Mair, who once published a
collection of excerpts from sex books.
   Peter Flaherty, chairman of Citizens for Reagan, recently sent
Wright a letter, with copies to the press, calling for the speaker
to fire the two men. ``Mr. Speaker, your office is the epitome of
sleaze!'' the letter concluded.
   Johanna Schneider, spokeswoman for House Republican leader Bob
Michel of Illinois, said the attacks on Wright's staff were coming
from ``a tiny segment.''
   Mack, she said, was well liked and ``I don't think anybody wants
to make an issue of that at all.'' But she said House Republicans
are united in their impatience with Wright's legislative tactics,
which the speaker himself concedes are heavy handed.
   The ethics case against Wright, timed to coincide with the
presidential election campaign, gives House Republicans the
opportunity to air their beefs nationally.
   ``It puts a focal point on the fact that the Democrats control
the House and they're doing a lousy job of it,'' says Steve
Lotterer, spokesman for the Republican National Congressional
Committee, which supports GOP House campaigns. GOP challengers will
point out that Democratic House incumbents voted for Wright for
speaker.
   ``Jim Wright is going to have a great deal of visibility as
chairman of the convention,'' he said. ``It think it has risen to
the point where people on Main Street know that Jim Wright has been
engaged in some very questionable activities.''
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, the likely Democratic
presidential nominee, apparently has not yet asked Wright to step
aside.
   ``I thought there was a presumption of innocence in this
country,'' he said last week when asked about the case.
   The ethics committee has said publicly it is looking at a half
dozen accusations.
   Those include whether Wright is accused of improperly lobbying
federal and foreign officials on behalf of Texas oil companies with
which he might have had a financial relationship. The panel is also
looking at whether he used undue pressure on federal authorities on
behalf of Texas banks.
   Wright's use of a friend's Fort Worth condominium as his home
while paying for the days he stayed there, but no monthly rent, is
also under scrutiny.
   But it's the speaker's book deal that's received the most
publicity.
   Wright in 1984 had a collection of his remarks and writings
printed by a Texas friend who had also done more than half a
million dollars of work on Wright's campaigns.
   The deal gave Wright 55 percent of the royalties from the $5.95
paperback when it wasn't sold through bookstores _ which accounts
for most of the sales from the 20,000 copies.
   The arrangement gave Wright $55,000 in extra income beyond the
regular limits in the House rules, because book royalties are
exempt. Many of the books were sold in bulk to political supporters
of the speaker, raising questions as to whether the book was merely
a vehicle to steer around the limits that apply to speech honoraria
and other methods of giving Wright money.
   While Democrats concede the rules may need to be tightened,
there appears to be a rising anger at the Republican attacks on the
speaker.
   ``There are House Democrats who really believe this is wholesale
partisanship of the worst variety, and they are genuinely angry at
Gingrich and those who support him,'' Rep. Pat Williams, D-Mont.,
said, adding that he expects to see ``attempts at retribution.''
   Wright himself has said he feels toward Gingrich as ``a fire
hydrant feels toward a dog.''
   Republicans say Wright's power may also be responsible for the
lack of defection by Democrats.
   ``You don't want to be the one two years from now who didn't
stand by the speaker, if the speaker survives until then,''
Schneider said.
 
</TEXT>
