<2ND_LINE>AM-Irate Inmate, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0683,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jailed U.S. Air Force Vet Breaks Handcuffs And Pummels 10 Inmates</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with inmate setting fire in cell</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 57-year-old Georgia man who was
jailed when his visa expired went into a rage Sunday and beat up at
least 10 of his fellow inmates, three of whom had to be
hospitalized, officials said.
   Franklin Coleman, a former U.S. Air Force lieutenant, was being
treated for burns he suffered when he allegedly started a fire in
his cell after beating his fellow inmates, authorities said.
   Coleman had been held in a detention center for three days when
he began shouting complaints Sunday about his living conditions and
the slow disposition of his case, immigration officials said.
   They said Coleman was subdued and handcuffed by guards and other
inmates after he tore off his shirt and smashed windows with his
fists.
   But the 6-foot-2, 198-pound Franklin broke the chain of the
handcuffs and began thrashing his fellow inmates, officials said.
   Immigration authorities said seven inmates suffered minor
bruises and three others had to be rushed to a hospital for
treatment. Coleman suffered several cuts on his hands, they said.
   Immigration officials subsequently transferred Coleman's
cellmates to the commission's main office building.
   Later in the day, authorities said Coleman was burned when he
set fire to the cell's mattresses and blankets. Arson investigator
Sgt. Rogelio Elorta said Coleman suffered second-degree burns and
smoke inhalation and had to be revived with oxygen by firefighters.
   Guards at the Commission on Immigration and Deportation's
detention center said they did not know Franklin's hometown. The
detention center houses foreigners facing deportation for various
offenses.
