<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope-Vietnam Bjt   06-19 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Vietnam, Bjt,0685</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Canonizes 117 Saints Martyred in Vietnam In Largest Such
Ceremony</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ROM1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II canonized 117 martyrs from
Vietnam on Sunday in an event that drew thousands of Vietnamese
refugees from around the world and irked that country's Communist
authorities.
   The Hanoi government had said that it wasn't against the
canonization _ the largest in Roman Catholic history _ but it
charged that Vietnamese emigrants seized on the occasion to make
anti-communist declarations.
   An estimated 8,000 Vietnamese, some of them ``boat people'' who
fled Vietnam since 1975, were among the 20,000 people who attended
the canonization Mass in St. Peter's Square.
   They later staged reunions in nearby restaurants or ate rice,
vegetables and grilled chicken from campers parked within the
Vatican's ancient walls.
   The pope said he felt ``profoundly and particularly close'' to
the estimated 3.5 million to 5.3 million Catholics in predominantly
Buddhist Vietnam.
   ``We can say that the blood of martyrs is for you, Christians of
Vietnam, a source of grace to progress in the faith,'' the pope
said during the noon Angelus prayer following the Mass.
   The Vietnamese were enthusiastic but orderly, joining in the
celebration without any apparent display of political sentiment.
   ``It's very special, it's great,'' said Tuan Nguyen, 14, who
left Vietnam eight years ago and now lives in Kristiansand, Norway.
A chartered bus brought him and two brothers, a sister and his
mother to the Vatican. Charters brought many of the Vietnamese from
their new homelands.
   Among those made saints were eight bishops, 50 priests and 59
lay people, including the mother of six children.
   The 96 native Vietnamese, 11 Spanish and 10 Frenchmen were
killed for their faith in the Southeast Asian land in the 18th and
19th centuries.
   Radio Hanoi, Vietnam's state radio, reported Thursday that a
Vietnamese bishop told Roman Catholics in his diocese not to
celebrate the canonization of the martyrs after officials told him
they were displeased with the ceremony.
   It said Bishop Huynh Dong Cat wrote a letter to priests and lay
followers also noting that before the Communists defeated South
Vietnam and reunited the country in 1975, June 19 had been a day
that honored the South Vietnamese army.
   The Vatican has said the date was a coincidence.
   Since the 1975 Communist victory, the Vatican has had no formal
ties with Vietnam.
   The Communist authorities had taken steps toward reconciliation
with the country's Christian minorities until announcement of the
planned canonization strained informal relations.
   The pope, who spoke briefly in Vietnamese to welcome the crowd,
alluded to the problems of the church in Vietnam and the delicacy
of its relations with the government.
   During the noon prayer, the pope spoke of a sanctuary to the
Virgin Mary of La-vang, which was burned during Christian
prosecution in the 19th century, rebuilt in 1901, and reduced to
rubble during this century's battles.
   ``Nevertheless, pilgrims today still gather around it, despite
difficulties, to pray to invigorate their faith,'' the pope said.
   After saying he hoped that the sanctuary would be rebuilt soon
``in a spirit of freedom and peace,'' the pope expressed a wish for
``national unity, as well as the true civil and moral progress of
the country.''
   The Vatican said 130,000 Vietnamese have died for their faith
since Christianity arrived in the late 16th century.
   In 1954, hundreds of thousands of Catholics fled south after the
country was divided into a non-communist South and communist North.
   ``The Vietnamese church, with its martyrs and by means of its
testimony, has been able to proclaim its will and its commitment
not to reject the cultural tradition and the legal institutions of
the country,'' the pope said in his homily, which was delivered in
French and Spanish.
   ``On the contrary, it has declared and demonstated that it wants
to incorporate it in itself, contributing with faithfulness to the
genuine building of the country,'' he said.
</TEXT>
