<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-88 1400EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Children'sHome     06-19 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children's Home,0768</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Stymied by Religious Homes' Exemption From Licensing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 50 youngsters from a fundamentalist
Christian boarding home shut down earlier this month are missing,
and officials blame Mississippi's exempting such homes from
licensing for the almost impossible task of finding the youths.
   ``We started out with an unknown number of children, and we're
still left with an unknown number of children,'' state Welfare
Commissioner Thomas Brittain said as Youth Court proceedings wound
down for the 72 children taken into custody from the Bethel Home
for Children in Lucedale.
   The home's operator, the Rev. Herman Fountain, refused to tell
state officials how many children he boarded, although the court
ordered him to provide a list. Fountain says the constitutional
separation of church and state exempts him from state regulation.
   ``You can't investigate in a reasonable manner unless you have
someone's name and something about where they came from and so
forth,'' Brittain said.
   Fountain told reporters that he had about 120 children living at
his 28-acre independent Baptist compound. With 72 in state custody,
that leaves about 50 unaccounted for.
   Youth Court Judge Robert Oswald ordered the state Welfare
Department on June 10 to take custody of the home's children,
ranging in age from 10 to 17. Oswald ruled they were subjected to
``physical abuse, medical neglect and detention amounting to
imprisonment.''
   Most of the children taken into custody were found roaming the
streets of Lucedale. They reportedly were told to flee the home
minutes after Oswald's order and before state welfare officials
arrived.
   About 50 of those taken into custody were returned to their
parents, who in most cases were required to sign an agreement that
they wouldn't be returned to Bethel, Brittain said.
   Parents of 13 of the children were refused custody because of
reports of child abuse before their children came to Bethel, he
said.
   Many supporters claim action was taken against Bethel to
pressure the Legislature into passing licensing laws.
   Brittain denies that. ``Absolutely not. We went into Bethel
because we had repeated reports of runaways and abuse.
   ``If this in fact helps lead to licensure, we'd be happy about
it.''
   Mississippi is among six states which exempt religious boarding
homes from licensing, said Jake Terpstra, licensing specialist with
the U.S. Children's Bureau of the Department of Health and Human
Services in Washington.
   Others are Louisiana, North Carolina, South Carolina and
Missouri, he said, adding that Florida requires registration, but
not licensing.
   About 20 unlicensed religious homes are discovered around the
nation each year in the 44 states requiring licensing, said Betsy
Rosenbaum, project manager of the Washington-based American Public
Welfare Association, a national organization of child welfare
administrators and agencies.
   ``Most states have had to deal with this,'' Terpstra said of the
oversight problem.
   Every state supreme court that has considered the issue has
ruled in the state's favor, Terpstra said.
   Nela Hughes, licensing specialist for Mississippi, says there
are 28 licensed residential child-care facilities in the state. She
estimates there are at least that same number of unlicensed
facilities.
   Some of the unlicensed facilities could be non-religious, she
said, because there is no penalty for failing to comply with
licensing regulations.
   Licensed child-care facilities must provide information about
administrators and the children in their custody and must have
written discipline and punishment policies, she said.
   ``This department does not recommend corporal punishment, but
there is no way we can prohibit it,'' she said, adding the law
forbids ``cruel and inhumane punishment.''
   Brittain said the Welfare Department has lobbied for licensing
reform.
   Hattiesburg attorney Dan Wise, a Youth Court judge who heard a
similar case two years ago involving the now-defunct Bethesda Home
for Girls in Forrest County, this week blamed legislators.
   ``The members of the Legislature who have obstructed passage of
regulations of 24-hour child-care homes by their unwillingness to
face up to and deal with a serious problem have caused the state of
Mississippi and mainstream religious homes to suffer yet another
black eye,'' Wise said.
   Paul Nunnery, executive director of the Mississippi Baptist
Convention's Baptist Children's Village in Jackson, said his
facility has voluntarily submitted to state licensing even though
it is exempt.
   ``We are Southern Baptists and believe in the separation of
church and state. We have not found that state licensing of our
children's home has interfered in the least with the practice or
tenets of our faith,'' he said.
</TEXT>
