<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0988</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock superstar Michael Jackson fulfilled a
childhood dream by visiting the widow of Charlie Chaplin at her
home in Switzerland during a break in his European concert tour, a
Swiss newspaper reported Sunday.
   The tabloid Sonntags Blick said Jackson visited Oona O'Neill
Chaplin on Friday at her home in Vevey, overlooking Lake Geneva. He
gave a concert Thursday night in Basel.
   The paper quoted Mrs. Chaplin as telling Jackson that he had ``a
lot in common with her husband'' because they were both born poor
and had to strive to achieve what they did.
   The paper said Jackson was a great admirer of Chaplin and that
he knew many details of the life of the silent-film comedian who
died in 1977.
   Sonntags Blick quoted Jackson as saying after the meeting, ``I
have just fulfilled my biggest childhood dream.''
 
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After completing a two-month, 1,581-mile trek
across the Greenland icecap, explorer Will Steger says he's
confident he and his team can cross Antarctica next year.
   ``Now I know we can do it,'' Steger said Saturday by telephone
from a lakeshore cabin in southern Quebec, where he and his five
crew members relaxed for the first time since leaving for Greenland
on April 13.
   The men and 30 sled dogs completed a south-north crossing of
Greenland _ which has been done only once before _ last week when
they reached the Humboldt Glacier. Most of the journey was
conducted without being resupplied with food or equipment.
   But the icecap expedition was just a warmup for a 5,000-mile
trip across Antarctica planned for 1989 and 1990.
   ``It was the same thing, day in and day out,'' Steger said.
``Sometimes the snow would be deeper, sometimes there'd be drifts,
but the terrain never varied at all.
   ``I knew it would be monotonous, and it didn't disappoint me.
Day after day after day. After a while it was kind of like a jail
term.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>McALESTER, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver Stone of ``Platoon'' fame spoke
out for a veteran who served with him in Vietnam in the platoon
that was the basis of the director-writer's Academy-Award winning
movie.
   Stone told the Oklahoma parole board Saturday that Toby T.
Sanders, convicted of burglary, developed his drug habit in the
platoon where both saw duty and were wounded in 1967. Sanders was
awarded the Army Commendation Medal for Heroism.
   ``I'm either going to be in a penitentiary all my life or be
drug free,'' Sanders told the board.
   The board unanimously approved Sanders' parole request on
condition he seek drug counseling. Sanders has been serving a
10-year sentence since 1985 for burglary of a doctor's office.
   Stone said he has heard that other members of the platoon have
been jailed or are dead from car accidents or suicides.
   ``I hope the board shows some mercy (for Sanders) as a Vietnam
veteran for what he went through,'' Stone said.
   ``You country owes you for your service,'' board chairman Carl
Hamm told Sanders. ``But by the same token, you owe it to your
country to obey its laws and rules.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Oak Ridge Boys country music group
and an ousted singer with the quartet are close to settling a $40
million lawsuit, the former member says.
   William Lee Golden, who was voted out of the award-winning group
a year ago, said an out-of-court settlement is being worked out.
   Wayne Halper, his lawyer, said Friday a settlement could come
within three-to-five days, but added, ``Sometimes these things take
longer.''
   Golden had been a member of the quartet for 22 years when the
other three ousted him in spring 1987 because of personal and
musical differences.
   He filed the suit for $30 million in punitive damages and $10
million in general damages.
   The Oak Ridge Boys are best known for their 2 million-selling
hit, ``Elvira,'' and ``Bobbie Sue,'' which sold 1 million records.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bottom line in business, government
and human dealings is trust, CIA Director William Webster told a
graduating class of mid-career executives.
   ``I've spent half of the last 40 years in public service and the
rest in the private sector, and there are some common principles,''
he said. ``And the most important one is that things work better
when people trust each other.''
   Webster spoke Saturday to 70 graduates from the executive
master's program at Northwestern University's Kellogg School of
Management.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adrian Dantley of the Detroit Pistons said he
doesn't care who was on the other end of the phone, all he wanted
was his insoles.
   On Friday in Los Angeles, Dantley got the telephone call he'd
been waiting for since Game 5 of the National Basketball
Association championships against the Los Angeles Lakers.
   ``They guy just called and said, `I have your orthotics
(insoles),''' Dantley said. ```I'm going to the airport and mailing
them right now.'
   ``I don't know who he was and I didn't ask why he took them. I
was just happy.''
   The Piston forward said that after Thursday's game, which
Detroit won 104-94 to take a 3-2 lead in the series, someone came
into the Pistons' locker room and swiped Dantley's shoes and the
insoles, which he uses because one of his legs is longer than the
other. He issued a plea for the souvenir snatcher to keep the
sneakers, but send back the insoles.
   On Saturday, Dantley got a Federal Express package with his wish
_ the insoles and a note reading, ``Good luck. Sorry A.D.! Meant no
harm. Go Pistons!''
   ``Now the series can go on,'' Dantley said.
   The shoes were replaced.
</TEXT>
