<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cambodia-Vietnam     06-19 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia-Vietnam,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cambodian Premier Vows Not to Give in to Guerrillas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodia's premier said anti-government
rebels are losing strength, and he pledged to resist their demands
for a new regime.
   However, Premier Hun Sen said in an interview seen Sunday in
Bangkok that the army faces a great challenge as Vietnam pulls out
its troops, which had bolstered his government.
   The official also played down fears of a takeover by Khmer Rouge
guerrillas, the strongest rebel force opposing the government that
Vietnam installed after invading in late 1978.
   Hun Sen's declarations came as his government, the three
guerrilla factions, Vietnam, and other nations prepared to attend
unprecedented peace talks in Jakarta, Indonesia, in July.
   The makeup of a new government was a key point of contention
that led to the break-off in previous talks between Hun Sen and
Prince Norodom Sihanouk, head of the resistance coalition.
   Hun Sen made no reference to the Jakarta talks but said ``if a
political solution could be achieved, the main thing we must strive
for is to safeguard the gains of the revolution. We are not so
naive or venturesome as to seek a solution which might lead to the
abolishment of the regime and state of the People's Republic of
Kampuchea,'' or Cambodia.
   The premier was interviewed by Vietnam's ``All People's National
Review.'' A text was carried by an official Vietnam News Agency
report dated Saturday.
   On Vietnam's planned withdrawal of 50,000 troops this year, Hun
Sen said, ``No doubt this is a big trial for the Kampuchean army
and people.''
   But he said his forces were gaining strength faster than the
largest guerrilla force, the Khmer Rouge. Diplomats are skeptical
of that claim.
   ``We may liken the situation to a short-distance race between us
and the enemy,'' he said. ``We have outpaced them by 10 yards, and
as of now we continue to push on a higher speed. So how can they
overtake us?''
   Vietnam's pullout, starting this month, and its pledge to
totally withdraw by 1990 have renewed concern about the return of
the Chinese-backed communist Khmer Rouge, which killed hundreds of
thousands of people and attacked the Vietnamese and Thai borders
before Hanoi ousted the group from Phnom Penh.
   Vietnam is believed to have already withdrawn some troops.
   Some diplomats say the Khmer Rouge has been avoiding direct
clashes to store arms and establish bases for an all-out offensive
in 1990.
   But Hun Sen said, ``In our view, the present low level of enemy
actions does not stem from, as others believe, their intention to
keep their force in waiting for the opportunity, but actually from
their dwindling strength.''
</TEXT>
