<2ND_LINE>AM-Amerasians,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Americans Seek Reunion With Children In Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired accountant from San Diego who
spent eight years in Vietnam is among four Americans returning to
the country Monday to try to retrieve the children they left
behind, a sponsor of the effort said.
   The four have written their Amerasian children to tell them of
their planned arrival in Ho Chi Minh City, said Bruce Burns,
director of the California-based Amerasian Registry.
   Burns, whose organization aids such reunions, said the four hope
to leave with their children for Bangkok in a week, then return to
the United States.
   The Vietnamese government has been cooperating and the four are
awaiting approval from the Thai government and the U.S. Embassy in
Bangkok, he said in an interview.
   Burns identified the four as Joseph Crotty of Redding, Calif.;
West Anderson of Poulsbo, Wash.; Verdun Andrus from San Diego; and
Nam Small, the Vietnamese-American wife of John Small of Westbrook,
Maine. She is trying to bring out the couple's son.
   Burns said Crotty, 62, a retired navy officer and former
California Highway Patrolman, left his pregnant girlfriend, Pham
Thi Tam, in Vietnam in August 1969. Their son, Khuc Thua Si, 18,
lives in Danang and was granted U.S. citizenship a few years ago.
   Burns said Anderson, 38, who works in a munition factory, spent
two years in the army in Vietnam. He brought his wife back to the
United States, but left behind their daughter, Nguyen Thi Lang, now
16.
   Andrus, 59, a retired accountant, spent eight years in Vietnam
working for a civilian architectural and engineering firm, Burns
said. He said Andrus has not seen his wife, Hoang Son Andrus, since
the communist victory in April 1975. She and their 14-year-old son,
Vo Thi Tham, live in Ho Chi Minh City.
   Mrs. Small's son, Nguyen Ngoc Linh, 16, lives in Can Thoc south
of Ho Chi Minh City. Burns said she has not seen him since 1974
when his medical examinations were not completed and she had to
leave to join her husband.
   John Small, 45, a postmaster, spent two years in the army in
Vietnam.
</TEXT>
