<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-Nevada 1stLd-Writethru a0718 06-19 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Nevada, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0718,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experts: Reservoirs, Rivers Will be Dry In Western Nevada By
Summer's End</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs last graf to CORRECT attribution to James.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By summer's end, this area of western Nevada
will be tapping its last available drops of water, and experts warn
there will be no reserve left if there's an unprecedented third
consecutive dry winter.
   ``The next couple of months are going to be spooky at least,''
federal Watermaster Garry Stone said Saturday.
   Irrigation ditches to farms and ranches will begin drying up
this month, and by August the Truckee River will be trickling
through Reno at one-tenth its current low rate, Stone said.
Reservoirs which also serve as recreational areas will be running
dry.
   ``The runoff is gone. We're not going to get any more storage
than we have today,'' Stone told a meeting of Associated
Press-affiliated radio and television reporters.
   With two weeks left in the July-June precipitation measuring
period, Western Nevada is on the verge of being the driest it's
ever been for that 12 months since records began at the end of the
Civil War, state Climatologist John James said.
   Western Nevada is dependent on the spring and summer meltoff
from winter's snowpack in the Sierra Nevada, which also supplies
much of California's water reserve. But that snowpack was half of
normal this past winter for the second straight year, and Stone
said water reserves in Lake Tahoe and other reservoirs are near an
end.
   ``By the end of August, Lahontan will be empty. That will end
any irrigation below Lahontan,'' he said. ``The vast majority of
irrigation above Lahontan will end in the next three weeks.''
   Lahontan Reservoir, about 35 miles east of Reno, is a narrow,
20-mile-long lake in the heart of one of Nevada's few agricultural
areas and a prime destination for boating, swimming and fishing in
this arid region.
   Stone said the Truckee, which runs out of Lake Tahoe to supply
the Reno area, is flowing at just under 500 cubic feet per second.
By Oct. 1, that flow will be down to 50 cfs, Stone said.
   While Westpac Utilities, which supplies water to the Reno-Sparks
area, has first dibs on that dribble, Bob Firth, the utility's
manager for water resources, said the company will have to turn to
limited storage in Donner and Independence lakes just west of the
California-Nevada state line and to its wells.
   ``I think we'll make it through, but if we have a third winter
with less than 70 percent of our average snowfall, we'll have major
problems,'' he said.
   Stone said he expected to be able to maintain the current flow
in the Truckee River through the end of July, but it ``will drop
off dramatically after that.''
   By the first week in August, ``most of the irrigation ditches in
the Truckee Meadows will be off,'' he said.
   Lake Tahoe currently is just 1.55 feet above its natural rim.
When it falls below that federally mandated minimum level around
Oct. 1, Stone will have nothing left to tap for the Truckee
Meadows, which encompasses the Reno-Sparks area.
   The region has received 3.13 inches of rain and snow since July
1 compared to 3.15 inches for the same period in 1882-83, the
previous driest July-June in the past 118 years, James said. The
average is 7 inches a year.
   ``With the growing population, we're going to be in a lot of
trouble,'' James said.
</TEXT>
