<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Rights     06-19 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Rights,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jurist Calls for Guarantees of Citizen Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet jurist called Sunday for strong new laws
to protect citizens' rights while the Soviet Union evolves into a
more open society under Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   A system of laws and judicial mechanisms should regulate
citizens' access to statistics and archives, guarantee open
information on changes in political leadership, and state what can
be published, legal scholar Yuri Baturin said.
   In material published in the Communist Party newspaper Pravda,
Baturin said new laws will have to make up for the Soviet Union's
lack of experience in guaranteeing citizens' rights.
   Publication in Pravda indicated there was some high-ranking
support for Baturin's ideas.
   ``With the background of our current political culture and as a
temporary measure, this kind of law is necessary,'' he said. ``In
20 or 30 years, if today's political tendencies don't change, the
need for them will be gone.''
   The Soviet Constitution theoretically guarantees broad citizens'
rights, but they often are ignored by Communist Party and
government officials.
   Both the czarist governments of the early 19th century and
today's Soviet government have censorship, but the czarist
governments openly published what the law was, Baturin said.
   In contast, ``it is almost impossible to mention in print our
Glavlit,'' the agency that decides questions of censorship, he said.
   The Soviet Academy of Sciences' Institute of State and Law has
presented to the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the country's top
executive body, a law ``fixing not only the basic rights and
freedoms of citizens and their associations, touching glasnost, but
the corresponding obligations of responsible officials and state
organs,'' he said.
   Glasnost is Gorbachev's effort to allow freer flow of
information and greater criticism on selected topics.
   In the past year, the Presidium has made no decision on the
institute's proposal.
   Laws and judicial procedures should guarantee access to
archives, statistics and ensure that citizens are given full
information about the appointment and firing of officials, Baturin
said.
   Eleven years since a constitutional article permitted
referendums on important national questions, a similar law is not
in force. A law regulating the mass media has been debated for many
years, ``not openly, but in the corridors,'' Baturin said.
   A program adopted by the party's policy-making Central Committee
for a party conference that begins June 28 bluntly tells Communist
Party members that they must obey the constitution and the laws of
the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880619-0056 </DOCNO>
