<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Fonda     06-19 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Fonda,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fonda Meeting Declared Start Of `Healing'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAUGATUCK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ``almost spiritual'' meeting between
Vietnam veterans and actress Jane Fonda, who angered them by
traveling to North Vietnam, has changed some feelings and led the
local VFW commander to take down an anti-Fonda poster.
   Fonda met privately for 3{ hours Saturday night with about 25
veterans from Connecticut and Massachusetts, where her plans to
film part of a movie this summer have been met with vigorous
protests by some veterans.
   The meeting came a day after she apologized on national
television for hurting veterans with some of her anti-war
activities, including posing for photos on a North Vietnamese
anti-aircraft gun during a trip to Hanoi in 1972 and saying
prisoners of war were lying about having been tortured.
   ``There seemed to be a genuine bonding between Jane Fonda and
the Vietnam veterans who were present,'' said Brian Powell, a
Naugatuck mailman who served in Vietnam in 1969-70. ``There was
finally some clarity about her feelings about why she did what she
did, why she went to Hanoi.''
   Powell, 37, said Fonda told the veterans that ``in her anti-war
passion she did some things that were very stupid and very hurtful
to Vietnam veterans.''
   ``The atmosphere at the meeting was almost spiritual in
nature,'' Powell said, adding that Fonda's message was that ``she
was not anti-veteran, she was anti-war.''
   Fonda said in a statement issued Sunday by her spokesman, Steve
Rivers, that she had wanted to meet with local veterans since
January, when protests heated up over her plans to film ``Union
Street'' in Waterbury, next door to Naugatuck, and Holyoke, Mass.
   ``I've met with Vietnam veterans many times over the years and
I've learned from that experience the importance of doing away with
preconceptions and stereotypes,'' Fonda said. ``That opens the way
for the healing process.
   ``I thought it was a very good meeting. We were totally honest
with each other, and I think we learned a lot about each other. It
was a very moving experience and I hope a helpful one for all of
us.''
   The meeting was set up by Rivers, Powell, Veterans of Foreign
Wars Post 1946 Commander Robert L. Genovese, and the Rev. John
McColley, rector of St. Michael's Episcopal Church and also a
Vietnam veteran. It was held at St. Michael's.
   James Sparrow, executive director of Vietnam Veterans Agent
Orange Victims in Stamford, said Fonda apologized ``a hundred
times'' while the veterans listened, then the veterans asked
questions.
   Genovese said that after the meeting he had a sign promoting
sale of anti-Fonda bumper stickers and a poster featuring a
caricature of the actress taken down in the VFW hall ``to go along
with the spirit of the evening.''
   ``Everybody learned a lot from everybody else. I'm not
completely convinced, but we both have a little better
understanding about each other now,'' said Clayton Hough, a former
Marine from Holyoke, Mass., who lost both legs in Vietnam and wore
an anti-Fonda button into the church.
   The anti-Fonda coalition held three rallies in Waterbury,
including one in April attended by more than 1,000 people. The
Holyoke Board of Alderman voted in February to approve a symbolic
resolution protesting Fonda's film plans in the area.
   The Waterbury Republican and American newspapers have printed
about 450 letters on the controversy, including letters in Fonda's
support from former first lady Rosalynn Carter and former senator
and presidential candidate George McGovern.
   The movie, ``Union Street,'' which also will star Robert DeNiro,
is about a working-class woman fighting her way up the social
ladder who teaches an illiterate man to read. Waterbury and
Holyoke, Mass., were chosen because of their working-class,
industrial characters.
</TEXT>
