<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Turkey-Ozal     06-19 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Ozal,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ozal Visits Wounded Party Delegates at Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ZEYNEP ALEMDAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Turgut Ozal visited wounded party
delegates at a hospital Sunday, and newspapers reported seven
underground groups claimed responsibility for his attempted
assassination.
   The 61-year-old leader, his right hand bandaged and in a sling,
told reporters he felt close to death when an escaped convict fired
at him Saturday, but he said: ``I was not afraid.''
   Ozal later told state television that all politicians had
enemies as well as supporters, ``so such incidents are
unavoidable.''
   The premier was delivering an opening speech at a convention of
his Motherland Party when a gunman fired twice at him.
   Police shot the assailant in the arm as people ran for cover.
Sixteen delegates suffered bullet wounds and four were bruised in
the stampede. Ten were hospitalized Sunday.
   Ozal uffered only a hand wound and completed his speech.
   A government prosecutor said the gunman, identified as
32-year-old Kartal Demirag, would be charged with attempting to
kill a member of Parliament. If convicted, he could be sentenced to
death, said prosecutor Ulku Coskun.
   Turkish newspapers reported Sunday that Demirag gave
contradictory testimony following his detention.
   ``I have psychological problems. I did not shoot to kill but
fired to get killed,'' he was quoted as saying.
   The newspapers said seven groups claimed responsibility for the
attack, including the outlawed Kurdish Labor Party, the Turkish
Communist Party and several organizations not previously known.
   The papers also said Demirag was a member of the now defunct
neo-fascist National Movement Party's youth organization before
1980.
   The party's youth branch, known as the Gray Wolves, was active
in a wave of terrorism that killed 5,000 people from 1978 to 1980
and prompted the military takeover of 1980.
   Mehmet Ali Agca, the Turkish gunman who wounded Pope John Paul
II in 1981, also was accused of belonging to the Gray Wolves.
   The newspaper claims could not be verified independently.
   After the shooting, police discovered Demirag was carrying $295
in West German marks and Turkish lira, according to the reports.
   ``The assailant is a prison escapee ... (who) carries foreign
currency. He needs to give explanation to these things. It requires
deep investigation,'' Ozal said.
   Police tightened security at the convention hall for the second
day of the Motherland Party convention, conducting searches and
doublechecking the identification of delegates.
   Demirag, 32, was convicted of attempted murder and sentenced to
10 years in prison last year, Ankara Gov. Saffet Arikan Beduk said.
Demirag had been in hiding since he escaped from a low-security
Mugla prison in January, the governor said.
   Beduk said the gun, a British-made eight-shot pistol, jammed
after two shots.
   Prosecutor Nusret Demiral said Demirag did not seem mentally ill.
   ``He might have given his early testimonies under shock, he is
not giving us trouble at the moment. But we are not going to reach
to a conclusion only with his testimonies,'' Demiral told the
Associated Press.
   Demirag spent Friday night in a hotel near the convention hall
under the name of a repairman in the southern province of Adana.
Policemen tracked down the repairman and sent him to Ankara for
questioning, the Anatolia News Agency reported Sunday. No other
details were given.
   Newspapers also reported that Demirag had one or two accomplices
who escaped later. But police officials did not confirm the reports.
   Newspapers also said the showing of the American movie
``Executive Action'' on state television Friday might have given
the idea to the assailant. The movie is about the 1963
assassination of President Kennedy.
   Ozal was first elected when a military government ceded power in
1983.
   The premier told state television some people may not like his
policies, which include an end to cigarette smuggling into the
country or his recent talks with Greece. The two countries nearly
went to war over Aegean seabed rights last year.
</TEXT>
