<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia-Expulsions, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0721,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deported Western Activists Condemn Police Action At Peace Seminar</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf pvs bgng: ``We are dismayed... with 4 grafs to
insert official comment. Pick up 6th graf: Joanne Landy...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 30 Western activists have been
expelled from Czechoslovakia for attending an unofficial East-West
seminar organized by Czechoslovak human rights and peace groups,
participants said Sunday.
   The expulsions came after police disrupted a series of private
meetings Friday and Saturday, detained participants, confiscated
materials prepared for the meeting and warned Westerners not to
continue the seminar, Western participants said.
   At a news conference sponsored by the International Helsinki
Federation, which monitors human rights in Eastern Europe, four
Americans who had attended the seminar said 32 people were expelled
Saturday.
   They were among 35 foreign activists from 16 countries who
attended the seminar organized by the Czechoslovak human rights
group Charter 77 and the newly established Czechoslovak Indpendent
Peace Association.
   In a brief report Sunday, the Czechoslovak news agency CTK
carried the first official report on the seminar and police actions.
   It said a group of Charter 77 members had ``tried to misuse
Czechoslovakia's active peace efforts for anti-socialist aims'' by
organzing ``a provacative seminar.''
   ``State organs prevented the provocation in a resolute way,'' it
said. ``Several foreign participants who repeatedly contravened
Czechoslovak laws had to leave the territory of Czechoslovakia.''
   A protest statement drafted by Western participants and signed
also by Czechoslovak activists said: ``We are dismayed and deeply
concerned at the arrest of 19 Czechoslovakians and one Hungarian,
and the police-state tactics of the Czehcolsovakian government,''
   Joanne Landy, of the New York-based Campaign for Peace and
Democracy _ East-West, said 17 people were detained when police
disrupted two workshops on the opening day of the seminar Friday.
She said they were released Saturday morning.
   A Hungarian rights activist, Ferenc Miszlivetz was also detained
Friday and deported the same day, she said.
   Landy said about 12 people were detained Saturday. A
representative of the Helsinki Federation said they had all been
released by 2:00 p.m. Sunday.
   Among the Czechoslovaks detained were Petr Uhl, a member of the
independent Charter 77 human rights group and one of the organizers
of the seminar; Jiri Hajek, a Charter 77 signatory and former
foreign minister; and Stanislav Devaty and Milos Hajek, both
Charter spokesmen.
   Rob Leavitt of the Massachusetts-based Institute for Defense and
Disarmament Studies said foreigners were sent away from the meeting
Saturday with a warning that they faced expulsion if they continued
the seminar.
   A third workshop on conscientious objection and alternatives to
military service was able to take place without interference. Brad
Knott, a peace activist from Washington D.C. who was at that
meeting, said police watched the apartment from a van in the street.
   Judith Hempfling from Amherst, Mass. said the protest statement
was read to about 30 people who gathered at an apartment Saturday
morning. She said it was circulated for signatures as police were
on their way upstairs.
   Leavitt said the foreigners present were ``escorted downstairs,
put in police cars and driven to the central police station.''
   He said 32 foreigners, including one activist from Yugoslavia,
were kept for about five hours in a central waiting room and were
then told they had to leave the country by midnight.
   ``The activities of the Czechoslovakian govenment fly in the
face of recent East bloc promises for democratic reform,'' the
protest statement said.
</TEXT>
