<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Travel     06-19 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Travel,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Passport Regulations Eased</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Interior Ministry has approved changes
that will make it easier for Poles to travel to the West, the
official news agency PAP announced Sunday.
   The regulations, which take effect Monday, will allow Poles
temporarily staying abroad to invite anyone to visit, rather that
just close family as in the past.
   All Poles must have some form of invitation to apply for a
passport, a regulation introduced after the imposition of martial
law in 1981.
   Poles still will not be allowed to keep their passports at home,
but prospective travelers will be able to pick up their passports
immediately after submitting a short request form.
   Poles still face obstacles before they go abroad because they
must obtain visas to visit Western countries. It can take weeks and
even months to obtain a visa for such popular destinations as
England, Italy or West Germany.
   About 6 million Poles will travel abroad this year compared to
5.2 million in 1987, according to the Interior Ministry.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said at a news conference
Sunday that lack of a computer system to keep track of passports is
the main reason Poland does not allow citizens to keep their
passports with them.
</TEXT>
