<1ST_LINE>r p AM-NebraskaSenate 1stLd-Writethru a0744 06-19 0772</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nebraska Senate, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0744,0791</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>All-Republican Board Declares Democrat Kerrey Nominee of
Independent Party</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Changes second reference to governor to Mrs. Orr, sted Orr.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROL ZUEGNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state's all-Republican Board of
Canvassers has declared Democratic former Gov. Bob Kerrey, who's
seeking the U.S. Senate seat held by Republican David Karnes, the
nominee of an independent party _ as the result of a primary in
which he received 20 votes.
   Under state law, Kerrey can only run as the candidate of one
party. Although it's believed he'll continue his candidacy as a
Democrat, Kerrey has said he won't immediately decline the
nomination of the New Alliance Party.
   At first, the board, which includes Republican Gov. Kay Orr and
four other high state Republican officials, said the party's
nomination was won by Ernie Chambers, an unconventional state
legislator whose political hero is Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi.
   Some observers believed that Chambers, the state's only black
legislator, might harm Kerrey's chances for election by drawing off
liberal and black votes.
   Although Karnes, appointed by Mrs. Orr in 1987 to fill the
unexpired term of the late Democratic Sen. Ed Zorinsky, made a
strong showing in the Republican primary, the most recent poll
showed him trailing Kerrey by 16 percentage points.
   On Friday, however, the board reversed itself and said Kerrey,
not Chambers, had received the most votes _ 20 _ from those
requesting ballots for the NAP. Chambers, the board said, actually
finished fourth with five votes; originally, it said he won the
nomination with four votes.
   In the Democratic primary, Kerrey had 153,500 votes, or 92
percent of the total cast.
   ``The situation revealed this week may possibly be no
accident,'' Kerrey said in a prepared statement Thursday.
   ``This doesn't appear to be a simple mistake,'' he added,
referring to Chambers' candidacy.
   Mrs. Orr, who succeeded the highly popular Kerrey in 1986 when
he declined to seek re-election, said the Democrat overreacted.
   The lesson from the confusion, she said, was that the state's
election laws need to be modified.
   ``Four votes _ certainly to my mind _ or 20 or 50 or 100 do not
duly constitute a viable nominee or candidate for a statewide
election,'' she said.
   However, state Attorney General Robert Spire, a Republican and
also a member of the canvassing board, said he would appoint an
independent special assistant to examine the activities of the
board.
   Kerrey's campaign manager, Bill Hoppner, said Friday the issue
isn't who was nominated by the New Alliance Party but how the votes
were counted.
   ``We need to know why the votes weren't counted correctly the
first time,'' he said.
   The New Alliance Party had only 14 registered voters in Nebraska
going into the May 10 primary. That number has reached at least 15,
since Chambers switched his registration from that of an
independent.
   In the May 10 primary, the party had only a space for write-in
votes.
   On a national level, the party's presidential candidate, Lenora
B. Fulani of New York, received $205,565 in federal matching funds
in January. She's seeking the party's nomination on some state
ballots and is trying to run under the banner of other political
parties in other states.
   Chambers, a barber who has a law degree from Creighton
University, said he wants to run for senator because both Kerrey
and Karnes are young _ Kerrey is 44 and Karnes is 39 _ and whoever
is elected may serve a long time. The 50-year-old legislator still
has several options to get on the November ballot.
   Chambers, who represents a predominantly black district in North
Omaha, said he also intends to run for the legislative seat he has
held since 1971. His reading of state law leads him to believe he
may run for both offices, he said.
   Nebraskans have learned to expect the unexpected from Chambers,
who wears a sweatshirt or T-shirt, jeans and tennis shoes in the
Legislature. He refuses to take the bar exam because he says the
state shouldn't have the authority to issue the license.
   Instead, he rents a chair in a barbershop in his North Omaha
district. But he spends most of his time in his Capitol office,
where mountains of newspaper clippings, reports and other papers
cover his desk. Posters and pictures of Khadafi decorate the walls.
   Chambers said he admires Khadafy's resilience, his never-say-die
attitude, and what he has done for the Libyan people in social
services.
   Last year, he successfully sponsored a bill to pay University of
Nebraska football players and athletes in the Big Eight conference.
However, Mrs. Orr vetoed it.
</TEXT>
