<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ArmsTreaty-Inspectors     06-19 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arms Treaty-Inspectors,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Reportedly Ill Prepared to Deal With Soviet Inspectors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department is ill prepared to
guard against security breaches when teams of Soviet inspectors
arrive on U.S. military bases July 1 as part of the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty, a magazine reported
Sunday.
   The pact, sealed in Moscow May 31 by President Reagan and Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, provides for the elimination of
nuclear missiles with ranges between 300 miles and 3,400 miles.
   It also allows the Soviets to send inspectors to 26 sites in the
United States and Europe to make sure the missiles have been
destroyed as agreed. The U.S. military will send inspectors to 133
Soviet-bloc bases.
   However, U.S. News & World Report said in this week's edition
that the United States does not have enough trained personnel to
prevent the Soviets from seeing facilities and equipment they are
not supposed to see.
   The magazine said the number of trained U.S. agents assigned to
the Pentagon's Technical Surveillance Counter-Measures Program,
which guards U.S. bases from electronic surveillance by hostile
intelligence agencies, has been cut from 160 to 32 in the past six
years.
   Only 10 of those agents are assigned to bases in the United
States, while the others are at U.S. bases overseas. However, U.S.
News said Pentagon sources, which it did not identify, said at
least 30 such agents are needed in the United States.
   The Soviets are arriving in less than two weeks, yet it takes
eight months to train a countersurveillance agent, the sources told
the magazine.
   The magazine also said mock Soviet inspections of U.S. bases
conducted by the Defense Department during the past four months
turned up a number of mistakes.
   U.S. officials playing the part of Soviet inspectors were able
to elude their trained escorts for up to an hour, copy down
classified information on data plates on weapon systems and enter a
sensitive weapons facility on the way to an inspection area.
</TEXT>
