<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Riots     06-19 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Riots,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll From Ethnic Rioting Reaches Nine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IQBAL JAFFERY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine people were reported dead Sunday
after rioting between ethnic Indians and native Pakistanis in the
southeastern city of Hyderabad.
   The riots started Saturday after buses filled with Pakistanis
arrived in Hyderabad, 84 miles north of Karachi, and opened fire on
the immigrants, witnesses said.
   The Indian Moslem immigrants came to Pakistan after its
partition from India in 1947 and are demanding recognition as a
separate ethnic group. A majority of them live in the southern
province of Sind, which includes Karachi and Hyderabad.
   Five people with gunshot wounds were taken to a hospital in
Karachi, doctors said. Another 35 were being treated at hospitals
in Hyderabad.
   After quelling the riots, police imposed a curfew on Hyderabad.
Businesses, offices and schools were closed and police in riot gear
patrolled the streets and warned residents to stay at home.
   The curfew has created food problems for the city's 1 million
residents, many of whom were not able to reach local markets.
   ``There is nothing in my house to cook,'' said Hayat Balock, an
elderly resident. ``I do not have (a refrigerator), so I buy
essential goods every day.''
   Residents contacted by telephone said police were warning people
to stay indoors or risk being shot.
   Ethnic riots in the past two years have killed hundreds of
people in Sind province and Karachi, a port city on the Indian
Ocean where the rival ethnic groups share cramped, squalid slums,
and compete for scarce jobs.
   In May, at least 30 people died in such clashes, and the
violence still flares every few weeks.
</TEXT>
