<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JailbreakKilling     06-19 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jailbreak Killing,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Kills Deputy, Sets Two Prisoners Free</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAK GROVE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man armed with a shotgun walked into a
sheriff's office Sunday and killed a radio dispatcher with a single
blast, then freed two prisoners in the parish lockup, authorities
said.
   Authorities mounted a massive search in northeast Louisiana for
an ex-convict they allege was responsible for killing Deputy Jeff
Gathings, 23.
   The suspect, 19-year-old Frank Bancroft, had been released from
jail Tuesday after serving a sentence for theft, said West Carroll
Parish Sheriff Gary Bennett.
   Set free were Sonny Caston, 20, and his brother, Frank Caston,
21. Both men had criminal records and were in the parish jail
awaiting trial on burglary and arson charges, Bennett said.
Bancroft and the Castons had been fellow inmates.
   Bennett said authorities are working on the assumption that
Bancroft plotted the break with the Castons prior to being released.
   Authorities set up road blocks around Oak Grove, located about
10 miles south of the Arkansas state line. Authorities found a
black Chevrolet pickup truck that may have been used by the three
men Sunday afternoon near the Castons' hometown of Lake Providence,
on the Mississippi River about 10 miles east of Oak Grove.
   Bennett said Gathings was alone in the radio room, adjacent to
the jail, when the killer entered.
   Inmates at the jail heard the blast of the 12-gauge shotgun and
saw Bancroft let the Castons out of jail, Bennett said. ``All of
them (the inmates) know him,'' Bennett said.
   Bennett said the door to the sheriff's office is locked at night
ordinarily; if normal procedures were followed, Gathings would have
had to push a button to unlock the door electronically and let any
outsiders enter. Television cameras allow the dispatcher to monitor
the entrance, the sheriff said.
</TEXT>
