<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Iran     06-19 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Iran,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliamentary Delegation Goes To Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four members of Parliament flew to Tehran Sunday
to seek improved relations with Iran and they warned against
raising hopes the visit might lead to the release of foreign
hostages held in Lebanon.
   ``We are cautiously optimistic,'' said Cyril Townsend at
Heathrow Airport before he and the three others boarded an Iranair
jet. ``This is very much a toe-in-the-water type operation.''
   Members of the delegation are Townsend and Robert Hicks of the
governing Conservative Party, Thomas Clarke of the Labor Party and
Lord Tordoff, a Social Liberal Democrat.
   Tordoff told an airport news conference that reports of the trip
had blown out of proportion the hope for winning the release of
three British hostages believed held in Lebanon.
   The Britons are among 18 foreign hostages held in Lebanon,
including nine Americans. It is believed most were kidnapped by
pro-Iranian Moslem extremists.
   Tordoff said the delegation does not know if it will discuss the
hostages during the visit to the Iranian capital.
   ``It's clearly something that is at the back of our minds and is
important in the general relationship between the two countries. To
say that we have a specific item on our agenda would be quite
wrong,'' he said.
   The legislators said they were not taking any messages from the
hostages' families.
   ``We are fully aware of how strongly they (the families) feel
and that's one of the reasons it would be quite improper for us to
build up people's hopes,'' said Clarke.
   The delegates said they did not know their program, how long
they would be in Iran or with whom they would be meeting, although
they expected to see Parliament speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani.
   The mission, arranged privately through the office of the
archbishop of Canterbury, Robert Runcie, is not sponsored by the
government and the delegates said their purpose is to try to ease
strains between Britain and Iran.
   But there have been many expressions of hope that an improvement
of relations might increase the chances for the release of the
British hostages.
   One of the Britons, 49-year-old Anglican envoy Terry Waite,
disappeared Jan. 20, 1987, in Beirut while on a mission for the
archbishop of Canterbury to help free the hostages.
   British television journalist John McCarthy, 31, has been
missing since Feb. 17, 1986, and Alec Collett, 64, a New York-based
journalist, disappeared March 25, 1985, while on assignment for the
U.N. Relief and Works Agency.
   An Islamic extremist organization reported Collett was killed,
but there has been no proof he is dead.
   Most of the missing foreigners are believed to be held captive
by the Hezbollah, or Party of God, a pro-Iran Shiite Moslem group.
   The longest-held hostage is American Terry Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press. He was kidnapped
in Beirut March 16, 1985.
   Relations between Britain and Iran deteriorated sharply last
summer after retaliatory diplomatic expulsions, the beating of a
British diplomat in Tehran and the shoplifting arrest of an Iranian
diplomat in Britain.
   Mohammad Jawad Larijani, Iran's deputy foreign minister for
European and American affairs, said the recent agreement to pay
claims for damages to each other's embassies was a sign of growing
cooperation.
   Larijani, speaking in an interview carried by Tehran Radio and
monitored in Nicosia, Cyprus, said the visit by the four Britons
could pave the way for cooperative exchanges in economic,
scientific and cultural matters.
</TEXT>
