<HEAD>Reagan, Mitterrand Shun Tough Issues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and French President Francois
Mitterrand sidestepped thorny topics on Sunday and used a 35-minute
meeting to discuss relations with the Soviet Union and problems in
education, a spokesman said.
   The two men, attended by senior officials, met before the formal
opening of the economic summit for a session French spokesman
Hubert Vedrine described as cordial and warm.
   Two key summit issues on which Reagan and Mitterrand have
conflicting views _ agricultural subsidies and Third World debt
relief _ were not brought up, Vedrine said.
   Reagan opened the session by asking Mitterrand, re-elected last
month, what his priorities would be in his second seven-year term,
Vedrine said.
   The French president said he would concentrate on education,
after which Reagan and Secretary of State George Shultz commented
on efforts to improve American schools, the spokesman added.
   Mitterrand and Reagan also discussed relations with the Soviet
Union, agreeing that disarmament talks should seek a balance in
conventional weapons in Europe and that Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev ``needs peace'' to make the changes he wants in Soviet
society, Vedrine said.
   U.S. Treasury Secretary James Baker III also participated in the
meeting, as did French Finance Minister Pierre Beregovoy and
Foreign Minister Roland Dumas.
   Mitterrand is staunchly opposed to Reagan's effort to get the
leaders of the seven industrialized democracies to endorse
elimination of farm subsidies. Mitterrand's major summit
initiative, a plan to ease the debt burden of the poorest
countries, has encountered U.S. opposition.
</TEXT>
