<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Summit-Britain-Germany     06-19 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Britain-Germany,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Thatcher Apologizes to Kohl Over Soccer Hooliganism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
apologized Sunday to West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl for the
hooliganism displayed by British soccer spectators in his country,
officials said.
   ``Mrs. Thatcher apologized deeply. She was very upset and very
angry,'' West German government spokesman Friedhelm Ost told
reporters. He said that in a nearly hour-long private meeting, Mrs.
Thatcher told Kohl she supports stiff sentences for people involved
in such rowdyism.
   A British official said Mrs. Thatcher apologized to Kohl ``in
forthright terms'' for the British rowdies' behavior during last
week's European Championship matches in West Germany. More than 50
Britons were arrested.
   ``The prime minister expressed her very great concern that this
sort of thing should have been inflicted on the West German
people,'' said the British official, who spoke on condition he not
be identified.
   He said Mrs. Thatcher told Kohl she hoped West German courts
would impose stiff setences and ``not be deterred at the prospect
of having to keep them (the jailed spectators) there.'' She noted
that under West European agreements, nationals jailed in a foreign
country could be repatriated to serve their sentences.
   Mrs. Thatcher also thanked Kohl, her spokesman said, for the
``firm way'' West German police dealt with the British hooligans.
   On Friday, the British Cabinet, after an emergency meeting on
the notorious behavior of British soccer fans in other European
countries, ordered the soccer authorities to take stern measures,
including ensuring that only listed club members are permitted to
follow teams.
   English football authorities withdrew an application for English
clubs to be allowed to compete again in Europe. They were banned
after a rampage in which 39 people were killed at a Belgium stadium
in 1985.
   Earlier, Mrs. Thatcher spent nearly an hour sightseeing in
Toronto's bay area under heavy security.
   Police on Saturday arrested on immigration charges an Irishman,
Michael Derek Collins, 31, who is suspected of having links with
the IRA and is wanted for questioning by police in British-run
Northern Ireland.
   Mrs. Thatcher also met separately with the new Italian Prime
Minister, Ciriaco De Mita, in what her aides said was mainly a
``getting acquainted session.''
</TEXT>
