<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-88 1752EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSWomen     06-19 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Women,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Best AIDS `Cure' Is Behavioral Education, Women In Medicine Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARGARET LILLARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Educating people that everyone stands at
risk of AIDS ranks as the most important duty facing doctors,
members of the American Women in Medicine Association say.
   Dr. Virginia Anderson, director of the Pediatric AIDS Study
Group in New York, told the gathering of about 60 female
health-care professionals that all categories of society face the
danger of becoming infected with HIV, adding:
   ``If the behavioral change could follow the education, there
need not be another new case of HIV,'' or human immunodeficiency
virus.
   ``Since we have nothing to treat (AIDS) with, our job is to
teach to change our behavior,'' association President Doris
Bartuska said.
   The doctors, meeting to discuss the impact of acquired immune
deficiency syndrome on women and children, were told by Anderson
and other speakers that people must be made to realize that HIV
exposure is not limited to homosexual men and to intravenous drug
users, two of the population categories at highest risk.
   ``AIDS is in the heterosexual population. It is in the
heterosexual female population, and it is not always in the groups
that have been high-risk groups in the past,'' said Dr. Mary
Guinan, assistant director for science at the Centers for Disease
Control in Atlanta.
   Guinan gave CDC data showing that of 4,738 reported cases of
AIDS in women as of April 30, the majority _ 52 percent _
contracted the disease through intravenous drug use; of the 12,684
heterosexual men with the disease, 69 percent contracted it through
intravenous drug use.
   But the percentage differed greatly when heterosexual contact
was determined to be the cause of the infection. In heterosexual
men, 2 percent contracted AIDS through sexual contact with the
opposite sex, while 24 percent of the women were infected the same
way.
   ``It's not kinky sex that puts people at risk,'' Guinan said.
``It's sex, normal sex ... and the number of sex partners.''
   She said CDC data also show that women are the source of 80
percent of AIDS cases in infants, infecting their children either
through childbirth or before birth.
   Guinan said the best method of fighting the spread of AIDS is to
fight for better sex education, ``which includes a healthy sexual
lifestyle.''
   She told the physicians to encourage condom use, but even
better, to call for celibacy or monogamy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
