<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bishop-Cubans     06-19 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bishop-Cubans,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholic Bishop Meets With Cuban Inmates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARKSVILLE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic bishop from Miami met
Sunday with Cuban inmates at the Avoyelles Parish Jail, where a
disturbance two weeks ago led to a nine-day hunger strike.
   Auxiliary Bishop Agustin A. Roman of Miami, who last year helped
end violent sieges by Cubans at two federal prisons, spent about 35
minutes visiting individual cells to talk with prisoners. He told
reporters later that the message he delivered was a sprititual one.
   ``We are not orphans and we have a Father,'' Roman said. ``We
have one Father and he is in heaven.''
   Last November, Roman helped negotiate an end to inmate takeovers
at a federal detention center in Oakdale, La., and a federal prison
in Atlanta.
   Roman said Saturday the United States must ensure that the Cuban
government will respect the rights of Cubans forced by this country
to return to their homeland.
   ``Every country should have the right to expel any undesirable
persons,'' Roman said. ``We're concerned about the situation in
Cuba. We are not sure human rights are served in Cuba.''
   The federal Immigration and Naturalization Service is reviewing
the cases of thousand of Cubans in the United States.
   When Cuban leader Fidel Castro agreed last year to take back
many of the Cuban exiles, it sparked the Oakdale and Atlanta riots
among detainees who wanted to stay in this country.
   Many of the detainees have served sentences for crimes committed
in this country and are awaiting word from the INS on whether they
must be deported, remain in prison, sent to halfway houses or freed.
   Since the riots, officials have dispersed Cubans to lockups
around the nation. Roman said Saturday that about 900 Cubans have
been freed as a result of the agreement that ended the riots.
   About 200 Cubans are at the Avoyelles jail, where more than a
dozen took over a large cell two weeks ago and held it for seven
hours. After deputies regained control, about 45 inmates said they
were going on a hunger strike to protest jail conditions and the
slow pace of INS review of their cases.
   The strike ended last week after inmates said they were assured
that Cubans' cases were being expedited, although INS officials
publicly said they made no deals.
   Roman said Sunday that the inmates he talked to ``are happy and
are waiting to be free with their families.''
   On Friday, federal officials announced that almost 1,000 Cubans
were being told their requests for freedom were being rejected and
that they faced deportation. Inmate Jose Lopez, 42, a spokesman for
the hunger strikers, said Sunday that 36 Avoyelles Cubans had been
rejected. But he said they can appeal that decision to the Justice
Department.
</TEXT>
