<HEAD>Colombian Guerrillas Attack Two Towns, Kill Eight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas on Sunday attacked
two Colombian towns, killing at least eight people including four
policemen, state and local authorities reported.
   Guerrillas stormed the town of Supia, 124 miles northwest of the
capital of Bogota, authorities in the state of Caldas reported.
They said the attack was by rebels of the Popular Liberation Army,
a Maoist organization.
   ``More than 100 armed guerrillas, women and men, joined in the
attack,'' a Caldas official said, speaking on condition of
anonymity. He said the guerrillas attacked two banks and the town's
main square where peasants were attending a local fair.
   ``They killed four policemen, one bank employee and a campesino
(peasant)'' in the one-hour raid and then fled, the official said.
He did not provide further details.
   Guerrillas from the rebel group M-19 attacked the town of Silvia
in the state of Cauca, 186 miles south of the capital, according to
local authorities. They said the gunmen robbed a farmers
cooperative and then left taking two rsidents as hostages.
   The captives were slain outside the town, said a spokesman for
the army's Third Brigade.
