<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Spoof     06-19 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Spoof,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warsaw Group Spoofs Balloting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Poland-Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,000 young people mocked nationwide
elections Sunday with a rally and march in Warsaw's Old Town. A
police captain responded with humor instead of force.
   The officer even loaned his loudspeaker to the demonstrators.
   The Warsaw youths reflected the Wroclaw-based ``Orange
Alternative'' movement that in recent years has held ``happenings''
that poke fun but do not directly attack the communist state.
   Dressed in mainly white costumes, groups of high school and
university students marched through the cobble-stoned streets
Sunday afternoon chanting ``Everybody to the polls'' and ``All
power to the councils.''
   They were referring to the elections to municipal and provincial
People's Councils.
   One man waved a red banner with a picture of Lenin and another
carried a flag of the Socialist Youth Union. Many held aloft copies
of the Communist Party newspaper Trybuna Ludu or folded it into
paper hats.
   At the Old Town's market square, the ``dwarfs'' _ as
participants called themselves _ swarmed around a parked police
command jeep. Rally leaders conferred with the police captain and
the two sides agreed on a 20-minute rally.
   The captain then loaned his loudspeaker to the ``head dwarf'' to
relay the message. ``Do you want to disperse in 20 minutes?'' the
rally leader asked. ``No'' the crowd chanted back.
   But appreciative of the unusual sight of a demonstrator speaking
over a police loudspeaker, the people began chanting: ``Captain
Captain.''
   The head dwarf then read a news item from Trybuna Ludu that said
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev plans to come to Poland in July.
The crowd roared its approval and sang a round of ``Sto Lat'' _ the
Polish equivalent of ``For he's a jolly good fellow.''
   The demonstrators next held a mock election, spoofing among
others government spokesman Jerzy Urban, before voting on a
candidate named ``Jan Council-less.''
   After a march to nearby Castle Square the captain finally got
the youths to disperse with this exchange:
   ``Dwarfs, listen, roll up the banners,'' the police officer said
``Let's bid farewell nicely. We'll give you all teddy bears.''
   ``Kiss, kiss,'' the demonstrators demanded.
   ``All right, senior dwarf, come over here and I'll give you a
kiss,'' replied the captain, who would not give his name to
reporters.
   ``Listen,'' he continued. ``Let's stop it. ... I haven't had my
lunch yet.''
   ``Good appetite,'' the crowd wished him back.
   When the captain persisted the crowd started chanting,
``Gargamel,'' the name of the villain in the Polish television
version of an American cartoon series about blue-skinned ``Smurfs.''
   ``Don't insult me,'' the blue-uniformed captain retorted,
showing he watches television too. ``I'm not Gargamel. I'm a
Smurf.''
   People in the crowd laughed and began going home.
</TEXT>
