<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Nancy,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mrs. Reagan Arrives Early At Dinner, Gets Unscheduled Tour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Nancy Reagan got an unscheduled tour
of the University of Toronto on Sunday after she showed up earlier
than protocol dictated for a dinner for spouses of leaders at the
economic summit.
   Mila Mulroney, wife of Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney,
as the hostess was the first to arrive at the dinner at the Royal
Ontario Museum.
   The visiting first ladies were supposed to arrive in the reverse
order of their husbands' seniority in office _ the procedure
required by diplomatic nicety.
   This meant Anna Maria DeMita of Italy first, Naoko Takeshita of
Japan second, Hannelore Kohl of West Germany third and Mrs. Reagan
last. The spouses of British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and
French President Francois Mitterrand did not come to Toronto.
   The plan went awry when Mrs. Reagan's motorcade drove into view
shortly after Mrs. DeMita's arrival and before either Mrs.
Takeshita or Mrs. Kohl had showed up.
   Aides to the firt lady who were waiting outside the museum
radioed a warning to the motorcade and it continued on its way.
   Wendy Webber, a spokesman for Mrs. Reagan, said the first lady
arrived at the time appointed, and she did not know what caused the
mix-up.
   At any rate, after Mrs. Takeshita and Mrs. Kohl had entered the
museum, Mrs. Reagan's motorcade rolled up for the second time.
   Asked what happened as she walked into the building, Mrs. Reagan
gave a diplomatic answer.
   ``We wanted to see the college,'' she said.
   The campus is near the museum.
</TEXT>
