<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GM-Undercover     06-19 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GM-Undercover,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: General Motors Assisted State in Undercover Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. helped the Maryland
attorney general's office in an undercover investigation of an
automobile repair business, according to a published report Sunday.
   The giant automaker made cars and transmissions available as
part of a nationwide program to help combat fraud in the industry,
The (Baltimore) Sun quoted David A. Collins, a lawyer for GM in
Detroit, as saying. He said the company has contributed to
investigations in other states as part of a three-year program that
has received virtually no public recognition.
   A consumer advocate questioned the ethics of GM's role because
of the company's financial interest in the auto repair industry.
The nation's largest automaker not only provides replacement parts
but also has paid out millions of dollars for repairs in a 1983
settlement of a case involving allegedly faulty transmissions in
about 5 million cars.
   ``From an attorney general's perspective, a lot of them could
use some help in ferreting out these bad repair shops, but I'm not
sure they should accept help from a business that has a financial
interest in it,'' said Russell J. Shew, a spokesman for the Center
for Auto Safety, an independent non-profit consumer group based in
Washington.
   ``It's kind of a muddy ethical question, no question about it,''
said Lawrence P. Mutter, executive vice president of the Automotive
Parts Rebuilders Association.
   GM cars and transmissions were among those used in a Maryland
sting operation resulting in consumer fraud charges against Cottman
Transmission Systems Inc., based in Fort Washington, Pa., according
to court documents cited by the Sun.
   The state attorney general alleged that 11 of the 13 Cottman
shops in Maryland violated consumer laws by making unnecessary
repairs, charging for work not performed and withholding cost
estimates until after work was begun on cars that had been in
perfect repair or had only minor problems.
   Attorneys for the Cottman chain have denied the charges.
   Maryland Attorney General J. Joseph Curran Jr. and William
Leibovici, an assistant attorney general who heads the office's
consumer protection division, declined to comment. They cited a
partial gag order imposed by a Baltimore judge.
   Telephone calls by The Associated Press to the homes of GM
spokesmen Donald Postma and John F. Mueller went unanswered Sunday.
   But Collins acknowledged that the carmaker had approached the
state of Maryland and offered to supply automobiles and
transmissions for sting operations in other states.
   Collins declined to say how many other states have used GM's
services in undercover operations, but put the overall national
cost at ``under $1 million and probably less than half a million
dollars.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
