<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Glencastle     06-19 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Glencastle,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Old Jail To Be New Home For Disadvantaged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An old city jail with medieval-style turrets and
thick stone walls would be transformed into a complex of 67
low-cost apartments for working poor people under an ambitious
project by an urban ministry.
   The Atlanta Stockade, once a debtors' prison, is listed in the
National Register of Historic Places. From 1897 until the 1920s, it
housed criminals. Except for limited use by the city's school
board, the building has been empty for most of the past 60 years.
   The renovated prison, to be called Glencastle, would be a
partial answer to the housing crisis faced by working poor people,
according to Renny Scott, project coordinator for the Family
Consultation Service.
   The apartments, he said in an interview last week, will be for
``precisely the person who's being priced out of the housing
market. There are people who spend 75 percent of their income on
housing.''
   In 1985, two developers bought the stockade property, which
includes a 25,000-square-foot warehouse _ formerly the prison
stables _ and an old blacksmith shop. They planned to turn it into
luxury condominiums.
   But they were unable to get the financing they needed. They
couldn't sell it to another developer. And they couldn't even tear
it down and start over; the cost of destroying the stockade's 2- to
3-foot-thick walls would have been too high.
   Family Consultation Service, located in the southeast Atlanta
neighborhood around the stockade, was looking for space to store
and sell home fixtures.
   ``We wanted the warehouse,'' Scott said. ``It was perfect for
what we wanted to do. But the guys that owned it said we had to
take the prison, too.''
   Officials of FCS, which helps inner-city residents, contemplated
uses for the building; Scott suggested housing. A local businessman
spent $210,000 to buy the property for FCS, and Scott, 43, was
named coordinator.
   ``It took us about six months to figure out which questions to
ask, and another six months to get them answered,'' he said.
``We're about 60 days away from the end of our pre-development
phase.''
   Individuals and groups from the Atlanta area have donated time
and skills to produce architectural plans and cost estimates.
   The total cost of the Glencastle project, including the
conversion of the blacksmith shop into a chapel and community
center, may reach $3 million, Scott said.
   ``We're looking for about one-third of it to come from in-kind
donations, from the plumbers and electrical people and so forth.
Another one-third we hope to get from corporations, foundations and
sources like that.
   ``The final third we hope to get from a public campaign,'' he
said. FCS wants to encourage people to purchase units for the cost
of their conversion, approximately $20,000, and donate them for
rental.
   Each of the one- and two-room efficiency apartments will measure
about 300 square feet and will rent for no more than $200 per month.
   Glencastle residents will enjoy a life far different from that
of their predecessors.
   Adult male convicts from the stockade were forced to work on
chain gangs. Female and young male prisoners cleaned, cooked and
worked the prison's farm.
   All the inmates toiled in a quarry near the stockade. Though
most had been convicted of minor offenses, prisoners were kept in
chains, which they forged in the blacksmith shop, Scott said.
   Despite its harsh history, the jail is a distinctive building. A
broad porch with five fluted columns stretches across the front.
Barred windows are generous; some offer a view of Atlanta's
skyline. Each corner sports a turret, once used as a guard tower.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
