<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran-Iraq 1stLd-Writethru a0774 06-19 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0774,0753</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Claim Capture Of Iranian Border Town; Iran Says Iraq Used Chemical
Weapons</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New info from Mehran and changes throughout with reports of
casualties, other claims.</NOTE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Baghdad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian fighters opposed to the regime of
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini captured this Iranian border town
Sunday. Iran claimed Iraqi army units attacked the town using
chemical weapons ``on a large scale.''
   The town, mainly a pile of rubble from earlier battles between
Iranian and Iraqi armies, was filled with cheering fighters of the
National Liberation Army including many women.
   Mehran, beside the border on the central front and about 100
miles east of the Iraqi capital of Baghdad, has changed hands four
times since the outbreak of the Iran-Iraq war in September 1980.
   On Sunday there was no indication of a major battle in the town
_ no bodies, no wounded, no destroyed vehicles or fires.
   Leaders of the anti-Khomeini Iranians said most of the fighting
occurred in the foothills of the mountains to the north and south
where artillery controls the town and that the offensive punched 12
miles into Iran at its deepest point.
   A press officer at the Baghdad headquarters of the National
Liberation Army told reporters the group's fighters ``liberated''
Mehran in a major offensive that started Saturday night.
   In a statement sent to The Associated Press office in Baghdad,
the group's commander, Massoud Rajavi, said the capture of Mehran
Sunday morning ``is a great victory and a basic step toward the
overthrow of Khomeini's oppressive regime.''
   ``Thousands of of enemy troops under Khomeini's command have
either been killed, wounded or captured,'' the statement said but
it gave no specific figures.
   Liberation Army leaders in Mehran said 1,400 Iranian government
troopers were taken prisoner. They acknowledged 48 of their
fighters were killed and said casualty figures were incomplete.
   A report by Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA),
monitored in Nicosia, Cyprus, said ``a large number of Iranian
Moslem combatants were martyred and injured when Iraqi warplanes
chemically bombed the Changuleh region east of Mehran.
   ``Earlier in the day, Iraqi warplanes had chemically bombed the
town of Mehran.''
   IRNA said Iranian special units were dispatched to ``neutralize
the cheical weapons using special techniques'' and that hundreds of
Iraqis were killed in fighting near the town.
   It also reported Iranian warplanes flew five missioons to bomb
Iraqi positions in the Mehran area.
   An earlier dispatch from IRNA said a six-pronged attack on
Mehran was repulsed and that Iranian troops were mopping up enemy
positions.
   Iraq denied its forces were involved in the attack on Mehran or
that chemical weapons were used.
   Iranian claims that chemical weapons had been used against its
forces in Mehran are ``nothing more than a pretext to explain away
a new military setback,'' said Latif Nusayyif Jasim, Iraq's culture
and information minister.
   ``The attack ... was mounted by forces of the National
Liberation Army of Mujahedeen Khalq, which have no chemical weapons
in their possession,'' Jasim said, according to a statement carried
by the official Iraqi News Agency, INA.
   Iraq said its combat aircraft flew 553 combat missions Sunday,
the highest number since fighting renewed last Monday with an
Iranian offensive in the Salamcheh region east of the southern
Iraqi city of Basra.
   Iraq also said its forces reclaimed 13 mountains in heavy
fighting along the northern border and that an Iranian helicopter
was shot down there. Iran denied the claim, saying all its aircraft
returned safely.
   The National Liberation Army statement said the Mehran
offensive, named ``Forty Stars,'' was the largest operation
undertaken by its forces and involved 22 brigades of combat and
support troops and covered a front 30 miles wide.
   But the statement did not say how many troopers are in each
brigade or give an overall figure of the number of fighters
involved.
   The group, formed last June, is built around the Mujahedeen
Khalq (People's Warriors) that helped Khomeini overthrow Shah
Mohammed Reza Pahlevi. It later was outlawed by Khomeini's Islamic
fundamentalists and created a base in Baghdad.
   Members of the Mujadedeen Khalq describe themselves as Islamic
socialists seeking a secular regime in Iran.
   Supported by Iraq, the National Liberation Army has been playing
a small but growing role in the war. Western diplomats in Baghdad
put the number of the group's fighters at about 15,000.
</TEXT>
