<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-88 1945EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WomanAbducted 1stLd-Writethru a0776 06-19 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Woman Abducted, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0776,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Body Of Missing Woman Found</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with cause of death, when body
was found; and to CORRECT location of county. Pick up 5th graf pvs,
``State police ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CORRY, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who called her banker husband and said
she was being held for ransom at gunpoint was found shot to death
Sunday in a wooded area, authorities said.
   The body of Sally Weiner, 37, wife of Pennbank branch manager
Harry Weiner, was found by a farmer about 8 a.m. in a clearing
about about 100 yards off a dirt road and five miles northwest of
Corry, state police said.
   Her body, which was fully clothed, was taken to an Erie, Pa.,
hospital for an autopsy, said Erie County Coroner Merle Wood. He
said the cause of death was a single gunshot wound to the head.
   ``I would say she died instantly,'' Wood said.
   No information regarding the time of death or the kind of gun
used was released.
   Dozens of state and local police officers and FBI agents had
combed Erie County in northwest Pennsylvania for the woman since
Friday afternoon. That's when she told her husband she would be
killed if he didn't meet an unspecified ransom demand, said Thomas
Doolin, president of Erie-based Pennbank.
   State police Cpl. Harold Eberhardt said Sunday he could release
no other information other than that the body had been found.
   Doolin said Mrs. Weiner appeared to be reading a prepared
statement when she telephoned her husband, who runs Pennbank's
branch in Corry, a community of 7,100 people.
   ``She said they were holding a gun to her and that there was a
death threat,'' Doolin said Saturday. ``She said ... he would find
instructions on what to do in a paper bag in the parking lot
outside the bank.''
   Weiner was told to buy a walkie-talkie, set it at a certain
frequency, and go to an isolated, wooded area outside Corry at 9
p.m. Friday, Doolin said.
   ``We followed the instructions and went to the designated place,
and they were supposed to make contact and they never did,'' he
said.
   ``In one way this thing looks to be well organized and in
another way it looks amateurish. This is a tiny little branch
office in a tiny little community, so it's hard to figure out why
this has all taken place.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
