<HEAD>More Than 3,000 Rally Against U.S.-Japan Security Treaty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 3,000 people marched in downtown Tokyo
Sunday in the annual protest against the U.S.-Japan security treaty
that allows the United States to maintain military bases on
Japanese territory.
   Police reported 21 people were arrested. They said that was the
largest number of arrests in a demonstration against the treaty in
at least five years.
   Many of the protesters wore helmets and snake-danced through
downtown streets carrying banners that said: ``Scrap the U.S.-Japan
Security Treaty.''
   The treaty, originally signed in 1952, allows the United States
to maintain military bases in Japan ``for the purpose of
contributing to the security of Japan and the maintenance of
international peace and security in the Far East.''
   It has been renewed on a year-to-year basis since 1970.
