<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Smugglers     06-19 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Smugglers,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Germans Convicted Of Smuggling Romanians To The West</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three West Germans were convicted of
smuggling Romanians to the West in the hidden compartment of a
truck for up to $12,000 each, a newspaper reported.
   The town court of Gyoer in northeastern Hungary sentenced
Siegfried Schwanke of Solingen, West Germany, to five years for
smuggling at least 20 people, mostly ethnic Germans, from Romania
to West Germany, the Magyar Nemzet said in its weekend edition.
   Roland Botschner and Heinz Christoph Dewenter received suspended
sentences of one year and eight months.
   The three belonged to a smuggling ring run by Hungarian-born
West German Ferenc Garbacz, who never went to Hungary. Ten other
West Germans were known to have worked for him, the paper said.
   The daily said Garbacz offered to smuggle relatives of people
settled in West Germany out of Romania for a fee of between $6,000
and $12,000.
   The West German smugglers met their clients in Hungary where the
Romanians had traveled as tourists, and then smuggled them in the
hidden compartment of a truck across the Hungarian-Austrian border
at Hegyeshalom, usually on Saturday or Sunday evenings when border
traffic is heavy, the paper said.
</TEXT>
