<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-88 2104EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Debt     06-19 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Debt,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summit Agrees In Principle To African Debt Relief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's seven richest countries agreed Sunday
in principal to grant wide-ranging debt relief measures to the
poorest countries of Africa, officials reported after the economic
summit's opening session.
   A British official, saying the United States had softened its
position, said the leaders reached a ``general agreement to
action'' based on a mixture of write-offs of loans, rescheduling of
debt and concessionary interest rates.
   ``The Americans at this summit have shown they are willing to go
further than they had previously,'' said an aide to British
Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson. The official spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Canada, the host, said the leaders of the United States,
Britain, France, Italy, West Germany and Japan had agreed they have
a responsibility to developing nations to find a solution to the
overwhelming debt problem.
   The British official said the summit leaders will send a ``very
strong signal'' to the Paris Club of Western creditor nations ``to
allow relief in these ways.''
   Canadian Finance Minister Michael Wilson said the final
communique will show ``clearly the direction we feel we should go
... and will provide industrialized countries, members of the Paris
Club, with flexibility.''
   The British official said the leaders' agreement meant that
creditor nations could choose from a menu of options outlined in
separate, but overlapping initiatives, put forward by Lawson,
Britain's top financial official, and French President Francois
Mitterrand.
   The British plan, first put forward and rejected a year ago by
most major creditor nations, called for a three-pronged approach of
write-offs, rescheduling and concessionary interest rates. The
French proposal allows creditor nations a choice of options.
   Before the summit, Lawson said in London that the American
attitude to Third World debt relief was inadequate.
   The United States has said it cannot legally write-off loans or
grant concessionary interest rates, but can grant extended interest
repayment periods.
   The Third World debt issue dominated Sunday's discussions by the
seven finance ministers meeting separately, and also apparently was
a major topic in the talks among the heads of government.
   French officials quoted Mitterrand as saying, ``the poverty of
the Third World destroys their societies and threatens ours.''
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said in an otherwise
upbeat speech that the poorest countries ``are not sharing in world
economic success and we must do something to help them.''
   The reported consensus means that each country can choose relief
measures that do not conflict with its laws on write-offs and
special interest rates. Fears that differing regulations in
creditor countries would mean some nations paying a much heavier
price than others to help the poorest have helped block previous
attempts at agreement.
   There was no word on any new initiative to help the
middle-income debtor nations, mainly Latin American countries,
which owe by far the most, but are not as badly off as the poorest
nations _ the countries of Africa below the Sahara desert.
   The debt of the poorest African countries totals around 85
billion dollars, a small fraction of the $1 trillion debt owed by
all Third World countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880619-0088 </DOCNO>
