<HEAD>At Least 130 Injured in Strike Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Violence during a nationwide strike by
private bus and truck drivers has injured at least 130 people and
damaged more than 100 vehicles, police said Sunday.
   Members of the Bangladesh Road Transport Workers Federation
walked off the job Friday to protest a proposal to increase from
five to 25 years, the jail term for anyone convicted of killing
people in traffic accidents.
   An average of two people are killed every day in traffic
accidents in Bangladesh.
   Nearly 100 people were hurt and 20 arrested Saturday when
striking drivers attacked state-run buses and other vehicles with
small bombs and scuffled with non-striking workers, police said.
   On Friday, 30 people were injured and 100 arrested, police said.
Fifty vehicles including passenger buses were damaged.
   The violence Friday and Saturday centered on Dhaka and
neighboring areas. There were no reports of violence Sunday.
   Salahuddin Ahmed, leader of the transport workers' federation,
said about 30,000 buses, minibuses and three-wheeled motor-scooter
taxis stayed off the streets. The job action also idled an unknown
number of freight-hauling trucks.
