<2ND_LINE>AM-Rain Ritual, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0802,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Medicine Man Tries To Cure Drought</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to add that sponsor grows plants commercially.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER C. KENT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLYDE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sioux medicine man Leonard Crow Dog, using an
eagle bone whistle and peace pipe, tried to summon rain Sunday for
this drought-stricken community.
   ``Four days from now, there's going to be thundering, lightning,
rain,'' Crow Dog said after performing a 30-minute Sioux ritual
that he says has never failed to bring rain.
   Cliff Doebel of rural Sandusky County, who owns a greenhouse and
plant nursery, paid $2,000 to bring Crow Dog and eight other
Indians from the Rosebud Indian Reservation in South Dakota.
   This northern Ohio town has received one-third of an inch of
rain in the past month. And the five-day National Weather Service
forecast held no chance of showers or thunderstorms until Friday.
   ``Without water, there is no life; without the direction of the
wind, there is no breathing,'' Crow Dog said. ``The Thunder Being
knows when there needs to be rain.''
   Crow Dog, 49, said his first rain ceremony was in 1953 when he
participated with his grandfather. He said he has done 126
ceremonies since then, all of which have been successful.
   Although Crow Dog performed no dance at the ceremony, the Red
Eagles, a Columbus, Ohio,-based Indian organization, performed
several folk dances unrelated to the rain ritual. The group also
chanted and played drums while Crow Dog, assisted by Sioux Indian
Chuck Grignon, blew a whistle toward the north, south, east and
west, toward the sky and toward the ground.
   ``We blow to the four winds, to the creator and Mother Earth,''
Crow Dog explained.
   The Sioux tribesmen who were to assist Crow Dog had car trouble
and arrived after Sunday's ceremony had ended, but they will assist
him in rituals to be held each day through Wednesday.
   Many of those in the crowd were dubious about Crow Dog's
rain-making claims, but said they were willing to try any solution
to end the drought.
   ``They pray by dancing, we pray by going to church. It's the
same God,'' said Mary Lou Noftz, one of the spectators.
</TEXT>
