<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ChemicalFire 1stLd-Writethru a0745 06-19 0824</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chemical Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0745,0842</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Head Home After Weekend Fire That Sent 275 to Hospitals</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to show 20,000 people home, 4,600 still
barred, plans to pour chemicals on factory; UPDATES with 22
firefighters hurt; Picks up 5th graf, ``This is ...'' SUBS 8th graf
``The fire'' pvs to rule out sprinkler as cause; DELETES 11th graf
pvs ``The corrosive'' with number of injured and condition</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 20,000 people returned home
Sunday after a two-day evacuation of neighborhoods choked by toxic
fumes from a chemical plant fire that sent 275 people to the
hospital.
   But 4,600 residents were barred from returning to their
neighborhood near the smoldering factory that continued to flare up
and spew deadly yellow-green gas. The plant makes chloride pellets
for swimming pools.
   Authorities said they would wait until Monday to pour 52 tons of
neutralizing chemicals on the remaining chloride. Firefighters
continued pumping water on the remains of the Advanced Laboratories
plant.
   The neighborhood around the plant was kept closed because small
explosions continued throughout Sunday. Anyone entering the area
was subject to arrest, officials said.
   ``I understand the difficulty of the inconvenience for the 1,800
homes involved ... but we think it's absolutely necessary to
conduct ourselves in a prudent manner,'' said Kevin Kennedy, an
aide to Springfield Mayor Richard Neal.
   Two schools, two housing projects for the elderly and a nursing
home remained off limits. Evacuees stayed for the third straight
night in city shelters.
   ``I'm miserable, inconvenienced, sweaty, hot, uncomfortable and
I want to go home,'' said Shellie Spencer Jr., 30, from his cot at
Municipal Hospital where he and his family stayed since early
Saturday.
   The last of the three weekend fires at the plant was finally
brought under control about 6 a.m. Sunday after a huge chlorine gas
cloud moved over this city of 170,000 people and forced the
evacuation of 20,000 to 30,000 residents from Springfield and
neighboring Chicopee.
   The corrosive fumes also sent 275 people, including 22
firefighters, to area hospitals with complaints of skin burns and
breathing problems, but only two residents were admitted, both with
respiratory problems. They were reported in stable condition Sunday.
   ``This is the worst public health and environmental disaster in
the 20 years I've been here,'' said John J. Higgins, regional
director of the state Department of Environmental Quality
Engineering.
   Fire Chief Raymond Sullivan called the blaze the largest in
memory and Kennedy said the disaster would cost the city millions
of dollars.
   The fires began when rain blew in a window in the two-story
factory and reacted with chlorine tablets in a hopper. The heat
from the reaction started a blaze at the pre-Civil War factory,
authorities said.
   The fire was quickly extinguished, but another began just before
midnight Friday about 30 feet away. Investigators initially
speculated that the sprinkler system that dumped 4 inches of water
in the plant started the second blaze, but then ruled that out.
   That fire appeared under control by noon Saturday, and 6,000
evacuees began returning to home. But water-soaked barrels of
chlorine exploded, throwing two firefighters against a wall and
prompting the extensive evacuation.
   The last fire was brought under control about dawn Sunday after
sending a huge gas cloud over the city of 170,000 people.
   Chlorine is used in diluted form for bleaching clothes and
cleaning swimming pools but is deadly in its pure, gaseous form.
   At the core of the fire was a room containing 600 to 800
barrels, each filled with 300 pounds of granulated chlorine that
was 85 percent pure.
   Firefighters pumped 14,000 pounds of water per minute in an
attempt to turn the plant ``into a big swimming pool,'' according
to Fire Department spokesman Giorgio Placanico. More than 50 tons
of sodium sulfate and boric acid were then mixed to pour on the
chloride in hopes of turning it into harmless table salt.
   Some of the chemicals were flown in overnight from Maine in
response to a plea from the Fire Department, but officials said it
wasn't enough. ``We don't have anything near the amount needed to
neutralize it,'' said Higgins.
   Although they risked reigniting the chloride, firefighters said
they needed to control the fire and dissipate the gas cloud with
water. ``If allowed to go on, the cloud would have stayed for
weeks,'' said Sullivan.
   At its height, the gas cloud measured two miles long and four
blocks wide and it drifted with changing winds. Its fumes could be
smelled as far as Palmer, 15 miles to the east.
   The cloud forced police and fire officials to move their command
post a half-dozen times, once at the order of panicked officers
yelling ``Get out of here!'' as the cloud rolled up the street.
   Police twice invoked emergency powers to forcibly remove elderly
tenants who refused to leave, according to Kevin Sullivan, an aide
to Neal.
</TEXT>
