<HEAD>Diplomat To Washington For Compromise Talks on Beach Strip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading Israeli diplomat will travel to
Washington this week for renewed efforts to settle a dispute with
Egypt over a strip of desert beach held by Israel, a Foreign
Ministry official said Sunday.
   The controversy over Taba, a 250-acre strip of land that
includes a beach resort, dates to 1982 when Israel relinquished the
bulk of the peninsula to Egypt in keeping with a 1979 peace treaty.
Both countries claimed the tiny enclave.
   In 1986 both countries agreed to send the issue to a panel of
international arbitrators, which was expected to announce a
decision this summer.
   An Israeli Foreign Ministry official said Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir and two top ministers decided Sunday to send Ronnie Sabel,
legal adviser to the Foreign Ministry, to Washington this week to
discuss the issue with American and Egyptian officials.
   The official said Israel agreed to negotiate a compromise
because Egypt dropped a condition that Israel acknowledge Egypt's
right to the beach.
   Israel radio said the compromise negotiations would take the
place of the arbitration by the five-member panel.
   But Egyptian Foreign Minister Ismat Abdel-Meguid appeared to
contradict the Israeli version when he told reporters Saturday in
Cairo that his country would accept the arbitration decision.
   The Israeli daily Davar reported last week that the arbitrators
would rule in Egypt's favor. Israeli officials refused to comment
on the report.
</TEXT>
