<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AdoptedKids     06-19 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Adopted Kids,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>4 Children Make A Special Father's Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For three men and their families the best Father's
Day present was meeting their newly adopted children Sunday after a
congressman cut through eight months of frustration and
bureaucratic delays.
   The four children from the Dominican Republic _ ages 16 months,
5, 7, and 9 years old _ entered the United States on probationary
visas after Rep. William Lehman, D-Fla., intervened for the parents
and adoption agency.
   Lehman blamed the delay on the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service misinterpretating a 1986 law dealing with
U.S. servicemen adopting sons and daughters born out of wedlock in
Southeast Asia.
   The INS said it was only following the law.
   In the meantime, the four children were living in foster homes,
and most of the adoption paperwork was completed.
   After months of appealing to INS administrators, Lehman received
permission to bring the children into the country on rarely granted
humanitarian parole.
   ``I think the INS is like many government agencies in enforcing
technicalities beyond their intent,'' Lehman said while waiting for
the children's arrival.
   Added Dianne Racheleau-Malaret, new mother of the youngest
child, ``I've dealt with bureaucracies before, but this is
ridiculous.''
   The 5- and 7-year-olds are a brother and sister adopted by the
same family. A third family adopted the 9-year-old.
   Lorri Kellogg, executive director of the Miami-based Universal
Aid for Children adoption agency, accompanied the children from the
Dominican Republic.
   ``The bureaucracy has to show a little more sensitivity,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
